{"title_page": "T\u00fcrbe", "text_new": "{{short description|Mausoleums of Ottoman royalty and notables}}\n{{Refimprove|date=October 2010}}{{For|the village in Bosnia and Herzegovina|Turbe (Travnik)}}\n{{Italic title}}\n[[File:Sarajevo gazi husrev bey mausoleum IMG 1279.JPG|thumb|The t\u00fcrbe of [[Gazi Husrev-beg]] (1480\u20131541) at the [[Gazi Husrev-beg Mosque]] in [[Sarajevo]]]]\n[[File:Divrigi,SitteMelikT\u00fcrbesi1.jpg|thumb|Earlier and more eastern examples have straight-sided roofs rather than domes, a Persian style. [[Divri\u011fi]], [[Sivas Province]] in central eastern Turkey. ?13th century]]\n[[File:Travnik 0492-border.jpg|thumb|The Grand Vizier's t\u00fcrbes the heart of [[Travnik]]]]\n[[File:M\u00f6m\u00fcn\u0259xatun t\u00fcrb\u0259si 2018.jpg|thumb|Momine Khatun Mausoleum in [[Nakhchivan (city)|Nakhchivan]] (1186\u20131187) ]]\n'''''T\u00fcrbe''''' is the [[Turkish]] word for \"[[tomb]]\".  It is related to the [[Arabic]] {{lang|ar|\u062a\u064f\u0631\u0652\u0628\u064e\u0629}} ''turbah'' (meaning ''\"soil/ ground/ earth\"''), which can also mean a mausoleum, but more often a funerary complex, or a plot in a cemetery.<ref>Meri, 270</ref> It has the characteristic [[mausoleum]]s, often relatively small, of [[Ottoman Dynasty|Ottoman]] royalty and Ottoman nobles and notables.\n\n==Characteristics==\nA typical t\u00fcrbe mausoleum is located in the grounds of a [[mosque]] or complex, often endowed by the deceased.  However some are more closely integrated into surrounding buildings.  They are usually relatively small buildings, often [[hexagonal]] or [[octagon]]al in shape, containing a single chamber, which may well be decorated with coloured tiles. A dome normally surmounts the building. They are normally kept closed, but the inside can be sometimes be glimpsed through metal grilles over the windows or door.  The exterior is typically masonry, perhaps with tiled decoration over the doorway, but the interior often contains large areas of painted tilework, which may be of the highest quality.\n\nInside, the body or bodies repose in plain stone [[sarcophagi]], perhaps with a simple [[inscription]], which are, or were originally, covered by rich cloth drapes. In general the sarcophagi are merely symbolic, and the actual body lies below the floor. At the head of the tomb in some examples a wooden pole was surmounted by a white cloth Ottoman turban (for men), or the turban could be in stone.\n\nEarlier examples often had two or more storeys, following the example of the [[Ilkhanate]] and Persian tombs on which the style was based; the [[Malek Tomb]] is a good example of these.  The Ottoman style is also supposed to reflect the shape of the tents used by the earlier nomadic ottomans, and their successors when on military campaigns.  Sultans often built their tombs during their lifetimes, although those of other family members, and some sultans, were built after their deaths.  Sultan [[Murad I]], assassinated just after his victory at the [[Battle of Kosovo]] in 1389, has [[Tomb of Sultan Murad|his t\u00fcrbe]] there, with his vital organs, while the rest was carried back to his capital at [[Bursa]], where he has another t\u00fcrbe.\n\n==Famous ''t\u00fcrbes''==\n[[File:Istanbul - S\u00fcleymaniye camii - T\u00fcrbe di Roxellana - Foto G. Dall'Orto 28-5-2006.jpg|thumb|The t\u00fcrbe of [[H\u00fcrrem Sultan]] (d. 1558) at the [[S\u00fcleymaniye Mosque]] in Istanbul, showing tiling, draped sarcophagi, one empty turban pole, and one with a turban (protected by plastic wrapping)]]\nThere are many famous ''t\u00fcrbes'' across [[Istanbul]] of the various sultans of the [[Ottoman Empire]], as well as of other notables from [[History of Turkey|Turkish history]]. \n\n===S\u00fcleymaniye Mosque complex===\nThe [[S\u00fcleymaniye Mosque]] complex has some of the most famous, including that of [[Suleiman the Magnificent|Suleiman]] himself (1550s), perhaps the most splendid Ottoman ''t\u00fcrbe'', and that of his wife [[H\u00fcrrem Sultan]], which has extremely fine tilework. Close by to the complex is the ''t\u00fcrbe'' of its famous architect [[Mimar Sinan]], in what was his garden.\n\n===Konya===\n[[Konya]] holds two earlier ''t\u00fcrbe'', with conical roofs, of the [[Seljuk Sultanate of R\u00fbm|Seljuk Rum]] dynasty in the [[Al\u00e2eddin Mosque]] (12th century onwards), and the ''t\u00fcrbe'' of [[Jalal ad-Din Muhammad Rumi]], which is a major [[shrine]] and [[pilgrimage]] point, just like the t\u00fcrbe  of [[G\u00fcl Baba (poet)|G\u00fcl Baba]] in [[Budapest]], [[Hungary]]. [[Bursa, Turkey|Bursa]], a capital of the earlier Ottomans before the conquest of [[Constantinople]], holds the ''turbes'' of many of the earlier Ottoman Sultans including [[Osman I]] and his son, the [[Muradiye Complex]] containing [[Murad II]] and many princes, and the [[Ye\u015fil T\u00fcrbe]] of [[Mehmed I]] (died 1421). This is a large three-story tower, and the (false) sarcophagus itself is covered in tiles. Unusually, much of the exterior is covered with undecorated coloured tiles.\n\n===Bulgaria===\n[[File:Turbe.jpg|thumb|right|\"[[Damat Ali-Pa\u0161a's Turbeh|''T\u00fcrbe'' of Damad Ali-Pasha]], [[Ottoman\u2013Venetian War (1714\u201318)|conqueror]] of the [[Morea]]\", in [[Belgrade]]'s [[Kalemegdan]] fortress. Note the [[hexagon]]al base.]]\nIn Bulgaria, the heptagonal ''t\u00fcrbes'' of dervish saints such as K\u0131dlemi Baba, Ak Yaz\u0131l\u0131 Baba, [[Demir Baba Teke|Demir Baba]] and [[Otman Baba]] served as the centers of [[Bektashi]] [[Zawiyya|tekkes]] (gathering places) before 1826.<ref>Lewis, p. 7.</ref> The t\u00fcrbe of [[Haji Bektash Veli]] is located in the original Bektashi tekke (now a museum) in the [[Hac\u0131bekta\u015f|town]] that now bears his name and remains a site for [[Alevi]] pilgrims from throughout Turkey.\n\n===Bosnia and Herzegovina===\nAt the peak of the [[Ottoman empire]], under [[Gazi Husrev-beg]] [[Sarajevo]], [[Bosnia and Herzegovina]], became the biggest and most important Ottoman city in the Balkans after Istanbul, with largest marketplace (modern days ''[[Ba\u0161\u010dar\u0161ija]]''), and numerous mosques, which by the middle of the 16th century numbered more than 100. By 1660, the population of Sarajevo was estimated to be over 80,000. Husrev-beg greatly shaped the physical city, as most of what is now the Old Town was built during his reign. The [[Gazi Husrev-beg Mosque]] (Bosnian: Gazi Husrev-begova D\u017eamija, Turkish: Gazi H\u00fcsrev Bey Camii), is a mosque in Sarajevo historic marketplace Ba\u0161\u010dar\u0161ija, and it was built in 16th century. It is the largest historical mosque in Bosnia and Herzegovina and one of the most representative [[Ottoman architecture|Ottoman structures]] in the Balkans. Gazi Husrev-beg's turbe is located in the mosque courtyard.\n\n[[Travnik]], in modern Bosnia and Herzegovina, became the capital of the Ottoman province of Bosnia and residence of the Bosnian viziers after 1699, when [[Sarajevo]] was set ablaze by [[Prince Eugene of Savoy]].  The Grand Viziers were sometimes buried in Travnik, and t\u00fcrbe shrines were erected in their honour in the heart of Old town of Travnik, where they stand today.\n\n===Hungary===\nThe t\u00fcrbe of Idrisz Baba stands in [[P\u00e9cs]], [[Hungary]] and was built in 1591. It features an octagonal base and domed [[sepulchre]], with [[ogee|ogee-shaped]] lower windows and circular upper windows on the facade. It is one of only two surviving t\u00fcrbes of its kind in Hungary (the other is the [[Tomb of G\u00fcl Baba]]), and plays an important role in the record of [[Turkish architecture|Ottoman architecture]] in Hungary.\n\nNot much is known about the Turkish person entombed in the t\u00fcrbe of Idrisz Baba; however, he was considered to be a holy man with the power to work miracles. It was later used as a storage facility for gunpowder. The t\u00fcrbe has been furnished with a mausoleum, embroidered sheet, and prayer mat by the Turkish government. Both the t\u00fcrbe of Idrisz Baba and the t\u00fcrbe of G\u00fcl Baba are places of pilgrimage for Muslims.<ref>https://www.iranypecs.hu/en/info/attractions/turkish-age/the-turbe-of-idris-baba.html</ref>\n\n==See also==\n*[[Gonbad]] and K\u00fcmbet, Persian and Seljuk equivalents.\n*[[Gongbei (Islamic architecture)]] (China)\n\n==Notes==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==References==\n*[[Michael Levey|Levey, Michael]]; ''The World of Ottoman Art'', 1975, Thames & Hudson, {{ISBN|0-500-27065-1}}\n*{{cite journal|last=Lewis|first=Stephen|year=2001|title=The Ottoman Architectural Patrimony in Bulgaria|journal=EJOS|location=Utrecht|volume=30|issue=IV|issn=0928-6802}}\n* Meri, Josef F., [https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=CJ8_4Kt0XUgC&pg=PA264&dq=qubba&hl=en&ei=USsETNmbH42cmwOSw-STAQ&sa=X&oi=book_result&ct=result&resnum=5&ved=0CDsQ6AEwBA#v=onepage&q=qubba&f=false ''The cult of saints among Muslims and Jews in medieval Syria''], Oxford Oriental monographs, Oxford University Press, 2002, {{ISBN|0-19-925078-2}}, {{ISBN|978-0-19-925078-3}}\n\n==External links==\n{{commons category|T\u00fcrbes}}\n*[http://www.cappadociaonline.com/turbe.html Cappadocia online]\n{{Islamic architecture}}\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Turbe}}\n[[Category:Ottoman architecture]]\n[[Category:Turkish words and phrases]]\n[[Category:Mausoleums in Turkey]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|Mausoleums of Ottoman royalty and notables}}\n{{Refimprove|date=October 2010}}{{For|the village in Bosnia and Herzegovina|Turbe (Travnik)}}\n{{Italic title}}\n[[File:Sarajevo gazi husrev bey mausoleum IMG 1279.JPG|thumb|The t\u00fcrbe of [[Gazi Husrev-beg]] (1480\u20131541) at the [[Gazi Husrev-beg Mosque]] in [[Sarajevo]]]]\n[[File:Divrigi,SitteMelikT\u00fcrbesi1.jpg|thumb|Earlier and more eastern examples have straight-sided roofs rather than domes, a Persian style. [[Divri\u011fi]], [[Sivas Province]] in central eastern Turkey. ?13th century]]\n[[File:Travnik 0492-border.jpg|thumb|The Grand Vizier's t\u00fcrbes the heart of [[Travnik]]]]\n[[File:M\u00f6m\u00fcn\u0259xatun t\u00fcrb\u0259si 2018.jpg|thumb|Momine Khatun Mausoleum in [[Nakhchivan (city)|Nakhchivan]] (1186\u20131187) ]]\n'''''T\u00fcrbe''''' is the [[Osman]] word for \"[[tomb]]\".  It is related to the [[Arabic]] {{lang|ar|\u062a\u064f\u0631\u0652\u0628\u064e\u0629}} ''turbah'' (meaning ''\"soil/ ground/ earth\"''), which can also mean a mausoleum, but more often a funerary complex, or a plot in a cemetery.<ref>Meri, 270</ref> It has the characteristic [[mausoleum]]s, often relatively small, of [[Ottoman Dynasty|Ottoman]] royalty and Ottoman nobles and notables.\n\n==Characteristics==\nA typical t\u00fcrbe mausoleum is located in the grounds of a [[mosque]] or complex, often endowed by the deceased.  However some are more closely integrated into surrounding buildings.  They are usually relatively small buildings, often [[hexagonal]] or [[octagon]]al in shape, containing a single chamber, which may well be decorated with coloured tiles. A dome normally surmounts the building. They are normally kept closed, but the inside can be sometimes be glimpsed through metal grilles over the windows or door.  The exterior is typically masonry, perhaps with tiled decoration over the doorway, but the interior often contains large areas of painted tilework, which may be of the highest quality.\n\nInside, the body or bodies repose in plain stone [[sarcophagi]], perhaps with a simple [[inscription]], which are, or were originally, covered by rich cloth drapes. In general the sarcophagi are merely symbolic, and the actual body lies below the floor. At the head of the tomb in some examples a wooden pole was surmounted by a white cloth Ottoman turban (for men), or the turban could be in stone.\n\nEarlier examples often had two or more storeys, following the example of the [[Ilkhanate]] and Persian tombs on which the style was based; the [[Malek Tomb]] is a good example of these.  The Ottoman style is also supposed to reflect the shape of the tents used by the earlier nomadic ottomans, and their successors when on military campaigns.  Sultans often built their tombs during their lifetimes, although those of other family members, and some sultans, were built after their deaths.  Sultan [[Murad I]], assassinated just after his victory at the [[Battle of Kosovo]] in 1389, has [[Tomb of Sultan Murad|his t\u00fcrbe]] there, with his vital organs, while the rest was carried back to his capital at [[Bursa]], where he has another t\u00fcrbe.\n\n==Famous ''t\u00fcrbes''==\n[[File:Istanbul - S\u00fcleymaniye camii - T\u00fcrbe di Roxellana - Foto G. Dall'Orto 28-5-2006.jpg|thumb|The t\u00fcrbe of [[H\u00fcrrem Sultan]] (d. 1558) at the [[S\u00fcleymaniye Mosque]] in Istanbul, showing tiling, draped sarcophagi, one empty turban pole, and one with a turban (protected by plastic wrapping)]]\nThere are many famous ''t\u00fcrbes'' across [[Istanbul]] of the various sultans of the [[Ottoman Empire]], as well as of other notables from [[History of Turkey|Turkish history]]. \n\n===S\u00fcleymaniye Mosque complex===\nThe [[S\u00fcleymaniye Mosque]] complex has some of the most famous, including that of [[Suleiman the Magnificent|Suleiman]] himself (1550s), perhaps the most splendid Ottoman ''t\u00fcrbe'', and that of his wife [[H\u00fcrrem Sultan]], which has extremely fine tilework. Close by to the complex is the ''t\u00fcrbe'' of its famous architect [[Mimar Sinan]], in what was his garden.\n\n===Konya===\n[[Konya]] holds two earlier ''t\u00fcrbe'', with conical roofs, of the [[Seljuk Sultanate of R\u00fbm|Seljuk Rum]] dynasty in the [[Al\u00e2eddin Mosque]] (12th century onwards), and the ''t\u00fcrbe'' of [[Jalal ad-Din Muhammad Rumi]], which is a major [[shrine]] and [[pilgrimage]] point, just like the t\u00fcrbe  of [[G\u00fcl Baba (poet)|G\u00fcl Baba]] in [[Budapest]], [[Hungary]]. [[Bursa, Turkey|Bursa]], a capital of the earlier Ottomans before the conquest of [[Constantinople]], holds the ''turbes'' of many of the earlier Ottoman Sultans including [[Osman I]] and his son, the [[Muradiye Complex]] containing [[Murad II]] and many princes, and the [[Ye\u015fil T\u00fcrbe]] of [[Mehmed I]] (died 1421). This is a large three-story tower, and the (false) sarcophagus itself is covered in tiles. Unusually, much of the exterior is covered with undecorated coloured tiles.\n\n===Bulgaria===\n[[File:Turbe.jpg|thumb|right|\"[[Damat Ali-Pa\u0161a's Turbeh|''T\u00fcrbe'' of Damad Ali-Pasha]], [[Ottoman\u2013Venetian War (1714\u201318)|conqueror]] of the [[Morea]]\", in [[Belgrade]]'s [[Kalemegdan]] fortress. Note the [[hexagon]]al base.]]\nIn Bulgaria, the heptagonal ''t\u00fcrbes'' of dervish saints such as K\u0131dlemi Baba, Ak Yaz\u0131l\u0131 Baba, [[Demir Baba Teke|Demir Baba]] and [[Otman Baba]] served as the centers of [[Bektashi]] [[Zawiyya|tekkes]] (gathering places) before 1826.<ref>Lewis, p. 7.</ref> The t\u00fcrbe of [[Haji Bektash Veli]] is located in the original Bektashi tekke (now a museum) in the [[Hac\u0131bekta\u015f|town]] that now bears his name and remains a site for [[Alevi]] pilgrims from throughout Turkey.\n\n===Bosnia and Herzegovina===\nAt the peak of the [[Ottoman empire]], under [[Gazi Husrev-beg]] [[Sarajevo]], [[Bosnia and Herzegovina]], became the biggest and most important Ottoman city in the Balkans after Istanbul, with largest marketplace (modern days ''[[Ba\u0161\u010dar\u0161ija]]''), and numerous mosques, which by the middle of the 16th century numbered more than 100. By 1660, the population of Sarajevo was estimated to be over 80,000. Husrev-beg greatly shaped the physical city, as most of what is now the Old Town was built during his reign. The [[Gazi Husrev-beg Mosque]] (Bosnian: Gazi Husrev-begova D\u017eamija, Turkish: Gazi H\u00fcsrev Bey Camii), is a mosque in Sarajevo historic marketplace Ba\u0161\u010dar\u0161ija, and it was built in 16th century. It is the largest historical mosque in Bosnia and Herzegovina and one of the most representative [[Ottoman architecture|Ottoman structures]] in the Balkans. Gazi Husrev-beg's turbe is located in the mosque courtyard.\n\n[[Travnik]], in modern Bosnia and Herzegovina, became the capital of the Ottoman province of Bosnia and residence of the Bosnian viziers after 1699, when [[Sarajevo]] was set ablaze by [[Prince Eugene of Savoy]].  The Grand Viziers were sometimes buried in Travnik, and t\u00fcrbe shrines were erected in their honour in the heart of Old town of Travnik, where they stand today.\n\n===Hungary===\nThe t\u00fcrbe of Idrisz Baba stands in [[P\u00e9cs]], [[Hungary]] and was built in 1591. It features an octagonal base and domed [[sepulchre]], with [[ogee|ogee-shaped]] lower windows and circular upper windows on the facade. It is one of only two surviving t\u00fcrbes of its kind in Hungary (the other is the [[Tomb of G\u00fcl Baba]]), and plays an important role in the record of [[Turkish architecture|Ottoman architecture]] in Hungary.\n\nNot much is known about the Turkish person entombed in the t\u00fcrbe of Idrisz Baba; however, he was considered to be a holy man with the power to work miracles. It was later used as a storage facility for gunpowder. The t\u00fcrbe has been furnished with a mausoleum, embroidered sheet, and prayer mat by the Turkish government. Both the t\u00fcrbe of Idrisz Baba and the t\u00fcrbe of G\u00fcl Baba are places of pilgrimage for Muslims.<ref>https://www.iranypecs.hu/en/info/attractions/turkish-age/the-turbe-of-idris-baba.html</ref>\n\n==See also==\n*[[Gonbad]] and K\u00fcmbet, Persian and Seljuk equivalents.\n*[[Gongbei (Islamic architecture)]] (China)\n\n==Notes==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==References==\n*[[Michael Levey|Levey, Michael]]; ''The World of Ottoman Art'', 1975, Thames & Hudson, {{ISBN|0-500-27065-1}}\n*{{cite journal|last=Lewis|first=Stephen|year=2001|title=The Ottoman Architectural Patrimony in Bulgaria|journal=EJOS|location=Utrecht|volume=30|issue=IV|issn=0928-6802}}\n* Meri, Josef F., [https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=CJ8_4Kt0XUgC&pg=PA264&dq=qubba&hl=en&ei=USsETNmbH42cmwOSw-STAQ&sa=X&oi=book_result&ct=result&resnum=5&ved=0CDsQ6AEwBA#v=onepage&q=qubba&f=false ''The cult of saints among Muslims and Jews in medieval Syria''], Oxford Oriental monographs, Oxford University Press, 2002, {{ISBN|0-19-925078-2}}, {{ISBN|978-0-19-925078-3}}\n\n==External links==\n{{commons category|T\u00fcrbes}}\n*[http://www.cappadociaonline.com/turbe.html Cappadocia online]\n{{Islamic architecture}}\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Turbe}}\n[[Category:Ottoman architecture]]\n[[Category:Turkish words and phrases]]\n[[Category:Mausoleums in Turkey]]\n", "name_user": "Tasase5", "label": "safe", "comment": "Osman is not a language.", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/T%C3%BCrbe"}
{"title_page": "Bible translations into Ge\u02bdez", "text_new": "[[File:Ethiopic_genesis.jpg|thumb|[[Book of Genesis|Genesis]] in Ge'ez]]\nThe '''Bible translations into [[Ge'ez]]''' date back to the 6th century at least, making them the one of the world's oldest Bible translations.<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite web|url=https://scottishbiblesociety.org/2017/12/geez-new-testament-ethiopia-new-translation-one-worlds-oldest-scriptures/|title=A New Translation for one of the World's Oldest Scriptures|date=2017-12-08|website=Scottish Bible Society|language=en-GB|access-date=2020-03-07}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.britannica.com/topic/Geez-language|title=Ge\u02bfez language|website=Encyclopedia Britannica|language=en|access-date=2020-03-16}}</ref>\n\nThe oldest translation of part of the Bible into Ge'ez are the [[Garima Gospels]].\n\n== History of the text ==\n{{See also|Orthodox Tewahedo biblical canon}}\nTranslations of the Bible in [[Ge'ez]], in a predecessor of the [[Ge\u02bdez script|Ge'ez script]] which did not possess vowels, were created between the 5th and 7th century,<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.britannica.com/topic/Geez-language|title=Ge\u02bfez language|website=Encyclopedia Britannica|language=en|access-date=2020-03-16}}</ref> soon after the [[Christianity in Ethiopia#Christian Roots|Christianization of Ethiopia]] in the 4th century.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.metmuseum.org/toah/hd/acet/hd_acet.htm|title=African Christianity in Ethiopia|last=|first=|date=|website=www.metmuseum.org|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-03-16}}</ref> The milestones of the modern editions were the Roman \"Editio Princeps\" of the New Testament in 1548,<ref>{{Cite book|last=Zuurmond|first=Rochus|url=https://books.google.be/books?id=nZIqKMRk6G0C&pg=PA464&lpg=PA464&dq=1548+aethiopice&source=bl&ots=Uv2U1kfgRR&sig=ACfU3U3RNEw0ZBEuCRcH_9sUFDE4hAWsxw&hl=fr&sa=X&ved=2ahUKEwjS-9Df95_oAhUCjqQKHfFAAQwQ6AEwAHoECAcQAQ#v=onepage&q=1548%20aethiopice&f=false|title=Novum Testamentum Aethiopice: The Gospel of Matthew|date=2001|publisher=Otto Harrassowitz Verlag|year=|isbn=978-3-447-04306-9|location=|pages=15|language=en}}</ref><ref>{{Cite book|last=Ehrman|first=Bart D.|url=https://books.google.be/books?id=guYq9rohFQ8C&pg=PA249&lpg=PA249&dq=Testamentum+Novum+1548+tasfa&source=bl&ots=JHwFebIlxy&sig=ACfU3U2nPlgSZ_oxO2lLG-OZXtbmq2KGgw&hl=fr&sa=X&ved=2ahUKEwictayi-J_oAhWPPOwKHdbUC08Q6AEwAXoECAkQAQ#v=onepage&q=Testamentum%20Novum%201548%20tasfa&f=false|title=The Text of the New Testament in Contemporary Research: Essays on the Status Quaestionis. Second Edition|last2=Holmes|first2=Michael W.|date=2012-11-09|publisher=BRILL|year=|isbn=978-90-04-23604-2|location=|pages=249|language=en}}</ref> and the critical edition of the New Testament by [[Thomas Pell Platt|Thomas P. Platt]] in 1830.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.tau.ac.il/~hacohen/NT/Information.html|title=Information and Notes|website=www.tau.ac.il|access-date=2020-03-16}}</ref>\n\nIn 2009, the [[Ethiopian Catholic Church]] and the [[Ethiopian Orthodox Tewahedo Church]] associated themselves with the Bible Society of Ethiopia to produce a printed version of the Bible in Ge'ez. The [[New Testament]] was released in 2017.<ref name=\":0\" />\n\n== Translations ==\n\n=== Garima Gospels ===\n[[File:Illumination-from-Abba-Garima-gospel.jpg|right|thumb|320x320px|[[Evangelist portrait]] of [[Mark the Evangelist|Mark]] from Garima 2, likely the earlier of the two Garima Gospels]]\nThe [[Garima Gospels]] are the oldest translation of the Bible in Ge'ez. It is the world's earliest complete illustrated Christian manuscript.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.ancient-origine.com/ethiopian-bible-oldest-complete-bible-earth/|title=Ethiopian Bible is the oldest and complete bible on earth. \u00b7|last=|first=|date=31 August 2016|website=Ancient Origine|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160901045246/http://www.ancient-origine.com/ethiopian-bible-oldest-complete-bible-earth/|archive-date=2016-09-01|access-date=2020-03-07}}</ref> Monastic tradition holds that they were composed close to the year 500,<ref name=\"Taylor\">{{cite news|last=Taylor|first=Jerome|url=https://www.independent.co.uk/arts-entertainment/books/features/unearthed-the-ancient-texts-that-tell-story-of-christianity-2019188.html|title=Unearthed, the ancient texts that tell story of Christianity|date=6 July 2010|work=[[The Independent]]}}</ref> a date supported by recent [[Radiocarbon dating|radiocarbon analysis]]; samples from Garima 2 proposed a date of {{c.}} 390\u2013570, while counterpart dating of samples from Garima 1 proposed a date of {{c.}} 530\u2013660.<ref name=\"Bausi\">{{cite web|url=http://www.ethiopianheritagefund.org/document-page-2|title=Ethiopia and the Mediterranean World in Late Antiquity: The Garim\u0101 Gospels in Context|last=Bausi|first=Alessandro|date=5 November 2013|publisher=Ethiopian Heritage Fund|page=2|format=Summary of conference proceedings|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170503173517/http://www.ethiopianheritagefund.org/document-page-2|archivedate=3 May 2017|access-date=3 May 2017}}</ref>\n\nThe Garima Gospels is also thought to be the oldest surviving Ge\u02bdez manuscript.<ref name=\"Bailey\">{{cite web|url=https://archaeologynewsnetwork.blogspot.com/2010/07/discovery-of-earliest-illuminated.html|title=\"Discovery of earliest illustrated manuscript,\" Martin Bailey, June 2010|author=A conservator at work on the Garima Gospels|first=|date=2010-07-14|website=|publisher=Theartnewspaper.com|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|accessdate=2012-07-11}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://ethiopianheritagefund.org/artsNewspaper.html|title=The Arts Newspaper June 2010 \u2013 Abuna Garima Gospels|publisher=Ethiopianheritagefund.org|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120501030359/http://ethiopianheritagefund.org/artsNewspaper.html|archivedate=2012-05-01|accessdate=2012-07-11}}</ref>\n\n=== Later translations ===\nGe'ez Bible manuscripts exist until at least the late 17th century.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.bl.uk/collection-items/ethiopic-bible|title=Ethiopic Bible|website=The British Library|access-date=2020-03-11}}</ref>\n\nIn 2009, the [[Ethiopian Catholic Church]] and the [[Ethiopian Orthodox Tewahedo Church]] associated themselves with the Bible Society of Ethiopia to produce a printed version of the Bible in Ge'ez. The [[New Testament]] was released in 2017.<ref name=\":0\" />\n\n== References ==\n<references />\n\n== Further reading ==\n{{Cite journal|last=Mikre-Sellassie|first=G.A.|date=2000-07-01|title=The Early Translation of the Bible into Ethiopic/Geez|url=https://doi.org/10.1177/026009350005100302|journal=The Bible Translator|language=en|volume=51|issue=3|pages=302\u2013316|doi=10.1177/026009350005100302|issn=2051-6770}}\n\n== External links ==\n\n* [http://ethiopianorthodox.org/english/canonical/books.html Canon of the Ethiopian Othodox Church]\n* [http://commons.wikimedia.org/wiki/Alwan_Codex Alwan Codex]\n\n'''Editions'''\n\n*{{Cite book|last=|url=http://archive.org/details/novumtestamentu00platgoog|title=Novum Testamentum Domini Nostri et Servatoris Jesu Christi aethiopice|date=1830|publisher=Impressit R. Watts|others=University of Michigan|language=German|year=|isbn=|location=|pages=|editor-last=Platt|editor-first=Thomas Pell}}\n*{{Cite book|url=http://archive.org/details/bub_gb_KPNa9Mc5gjYC|title=Testamentum Nouum cum epistola Pauli ad Hebreos tantum, cum concordantijs euangelistarum Eusebij & numeratione omnium verborum eorundem. Missale cum benedictione incensi cer\u00e6 ... Chaldea, qu\u00e6 omnia frater Petrus Ethyops ... imprimi curauit|date=1548|others=National Central Library of Rome|language=English}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Bible Translations Into Geez}}\n[[Category:Apocrypha]]\n[[Category:Christianity in Ethiopia]]\n[[Category:Bible versions and translations]]\n[[Category:Texts in Ge'ez]]\n", "text_old": "[[File:Ethiopic_genesis.jpg|thumb|Genesis in Ge'ez]]\nThe Bible translations into [[Ge'ez]] date back to the 6th century at least, making them the one of the world's oldest Bible translations.<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite web|url=https://scottishbiblesociety.org/2017/12/geez-new-testament-ethiopia-new-translation-one-worlds-oldest-scriptures/|title=A New Translation for one of the World's Oldest Scriptures|date=2017-12-08|website=Scottish Bible Society|language=en-GB|access-date=2020-03-07}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.britannica.com/topic/Geez-language|title=Ge\u02bfez language|website=Encyclopedia Britannica|language=en|access-date=2020-03-16}}</ref>\n\nThe oldest translation of part of the Bible into Ge'ez are the [[Garima Gospels]].\n\n== History of the text ==\n{{See also|Orthodox Tewahedo biblical canon}}\nTranslations of the Bible in [[Ge'ez]], in a predecessor of the [[Ge\u02bdez script|Ge'ez script]] which did not possess vowels, were created between the 5th and 7th century,<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.britannica.com/topic/Geez-language|title=Ge\u02bfez language|website=Encyclopedia Britannica|language=en|access-date=2020-03-16}}</ref> soon after the [[Christianity in Ethiopia#Christian Roots|Christianization of Ethiopia]] in the 4th century.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.metmuseum.org/toah/hd/acet/hd_acet.htm|title=African Christianity in Ethiopia|last=|first=|date=|website=www.metmuseum.org|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-03-16}}</ref> The milestones of the modern editions were the Roman \"Editio Princeps\" of the New Testament in 1548,<ref>{{Cite book|last=Zuurmond|first=Rochus|url=https://books.google.be/books?id=nZIqKMRk6G0C&pg=PA464&lpg=PA464&dq=1548+aethiopice&source=bl&ots=Uv2U1kfgRR&sig=ACfU3U3RNEw0ZBEuCRcH_9sUFDE4hAWsxw&hl=fr&sa=X&ved=2ahUKEwjS-9Df95_oAhUCjqQKHfFAAQwQ6AEwAHoECAcQAQ#v=onepage&q=1548%20aethiopice&f=false|title=Novum Testamentum Aethiopice: The Gospel of Matthew|date=2001|publisher=Otto Harrassowitz Verlag|year=|isbn=978-3-447-04306-9|location=|pages=15|language=en}}</ref><ref>{{Cite book|last=Ehrman|first=Bart D.|url=https://books.google.be/books?id=guYq9rohFQ8C&pg=PA249&lpg=PA249&dq=Testamentum+Novum+1548+tasfa&source=bl&ots=JHwFebIlxy&sig=ACfU3U2nPlgSZ_oxO2lLG-OZXtbmq2KGgw&hl=fr&sa=X&ved=2ahUKEwictayi-J_oAhWPPOwKHdbUC08Q6AEwAXoECAkQAQ#v=onepage&q=Testamentum%20Novum%201548%20tasfa&f=false|title=The Text of the New Testament in Contemporary Research: Essays on the Status Quaestionis. Second Edition|last2=Holmes|first2=Michael W.|date=2012-11-09|publisher=BRILL|year=|isbn=978-90-04-23604-2|location=|pages=249|language=en}}</ref> and the critical edition of the New Testament by [[Thomas Pell Platt|Thomas P. Platt]] in 1830.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.tau.ac.il/~hacohen/NT/Information.html|title=Information and Notes|website=www.tau.ac.il|access-date=2020-03-16}}</ref>\n\nIn 2009, the [[Ethiopian Catholic Church]] and the [[Ethiopian Orthodox Tewahedo Church]] associated themselves with the Bible Society of Ethiopia to produce a printed version of the Bible in Ge'ez. The [[New Testament]] was released in 2017.<ref name=\":0\" />\n\n== Translations ==\n\n=== Garima Gospels ===\n[[File:Illumination-from-Abba-Garima-gospel.jpg|right|thumb|320x320px|[[Evangelist portrait]] of [[Mark the Evangelist|Mark]] from Garima 2, likely the earlier of the two Garima Gospels]]\nThe [[Garima Gospels]] are the oldest translation of the Bible in Ge'ez. It is the world's earliest complete illustrated Christian manuscript.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.ancient-origine.com/ethiopian-bible-oldest-complete-bible-earth/|title=Ethiopian Bible is the oldest and complete bible on earth. \u00b7|last=|first=|date=31 August 2016|website=Ancient Origine|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160901045246/http://www.ancient-origine.com/ethiopian-bible-oldest-complete-bible-earth/|archive-date=2016-09-01|access-date=2020-03-07}}</ref> Monastic tradition holds that they were composed close to the year 500,<ref name=\"Taylor\">{{cite news|last=Taylor|first=Jerome|url=https://www.independent.co.uk/arts-entertainment/books/features/unearthed-the-ancient-texts-that-tell-story-of-christianity-2019188.html|title=Unearthed, the ancient texts that tell story of Christianity|date=6 July 2010|work=[[The Independent]]}}</ref> a date supported by recent [[Radiocarbon dating|radiocarbon analysis]]; samples from Garima 2 proposed a date of {{c.}} 390\u2013570, while counterpart dating of samples from Garima 1 proposed a date of {{c.}} 530\u2013660.<ref name=\"Bausi\">{{cite web|url=http://www.ethiopianheritagefund.org/document-page-2|title=Ethiopia and the Mediterranean World in Late Antiquity: The Garim\u0101 Gospels in Context|last=Bausi|first=Alessandro|date=5 November 2013|publisher=Ethiopian Heritage Fund|page=2|format=Summary of conference proceedings|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170503173517/http://www.ethiopianheritagefund.org/document-page-2|archivedate=3 May 2017|access-date=3 May 2017}}</ref>\n\nThe Garima Gospels is also thought to be the oldest surviving Ge\u02bdez manuscript.<ref name=\"Bailey\">{{cite web|url=https://archaeologynewsnetwork.blogspot.com/2010/07/discovery-of-earliest-illuminated.html|title=\"Discovery of earliest illustrated manuscript,\" Martin Bailey, June 2010|author=A conservator at work on the Garima Gospels|first=|date=2010-07-14|website=|publisher=Theartnewspaper.com|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|accessdate=2012-07-11}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://ethiopianheritagefund.org/artsNewspaper.html|title=The Arts Newspaper June 2010 \u2013 Abuna Garima Gospels|publisher=Ethiopianheritagefund.org|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120501030359/http://ethiopianheritagefund.org/artsNewspaper.html|archivedate=2012-05-01|accessdate=2012-07-11}}</ref>\n\n=== Later translations ===\nGe'ez Bible manuscripts exist until at least the late 17th century.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.bl.uk/collection-items/ethiopic-bible|title=Ethiopic Bible|website=The British Library|access-date=2020-03-11}}</ref>\n\nIn 2009, the [[Ethiopian Catholic Church]] and the [[Ethiopian Orthodox Tewahedo Church]] associated themselves with the Bible Society of Ethiopia to produce a printed version of the Bible in Ge'ez. The [[New Testament]] was released in 2017.<ref name=\":0\" />\n\n== References ==\n<references />\n\n== Further reading ==\n{{Cite journal|last=Mikre-Sellassie|first=G.A.|date=2000-07-01|title=The Early Translation of the Bible into Ethiopic/Geez|url=https://doi.org/10.1177/026009350005100302|journal=The Bible Translator|language=en|volume=51|issue=3|pages=302\u2013316|doi=10.1177/026009350005100302|issn=2051-6770}}\n\n== External links ==\n\n* [http://ethiopianorthodox.org/english/canonical/books.html Canon of the Ethiopian Othodox Church]\n* [http://commons.wikimedia.org/wiki/Alwan_Codex Alwan Codex]\n\n'''Editions'''\n\n*{{Cite book|last=|url=http://archive.org/details/novumtestamentu00platgoog|title=Novum Testamentum Domini Nostri et Servatoris Jesu Christi aethiopice|date=1830|publisher=Impressit R. Watts|others=University of Michigan|language=German|year=|isbn=|location=|pages=|editor-last=Platt|editor-first=Thomas Pell}}\n*{{Cite book|url=http://archive.org/details/bub_gb_KPNa9Mc5gjYC|title=Testamentum Nouum cum epistola Pauli ad Hebreos tantum, cum concordantijs euangelistarum Eusebij & numeratione omnium verborum eorundem. Missale cum benedictione incensi cer\u00e6 ... Chaldea, qu\u00e6 omnia frater Petrus Ethyops ... imprimi curauit|date=1548|others=National Central Library of Rome|language=English}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Bible Translations Into Geez}}\n[[Category:Apocrypha]]\n[[Category:Christianity in Ethiopia]]\n[[Category:Bible versions and translations]]\n[[Category:Texts in Ge'ez]]\n", "name_user": "MartinPoulter", "label": "safe", "comment": "bold + wikilink", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Bible_translations_into_Ge%CA%BDez"}
{"title_page": "Post-metal", "text_new": "{{Multiple issues|\n{{essay-like|date=September 2018}}\n{{synthesis|article|date=September 2018}}\n}}\n\n{{Infobox music genre\n| name = Post-metal\n| bgcolor = #BB0022\n| color = white\n| other_names = *Art metal\n*metalgaze\n| stylistic_origins = <!-- please do not make unexplained changes -->{{hlist|[[Extreme metal]]|[[experimental music|experimental]]|[[post-rock]]|[[post-hardcore]]}}\n| cultural_origins = 1990s, [[United States]] and [[England]]\n| instruments = {{hlist|[[Electric guitar]]|[[Bass guitar|bass]]|[[Drum kit|drums]]}}\n| derivatives = [[Blackgaze]]\n| regional_scenes = \n| local_scenes = \n| other_topics = * [[Alternative metal]]\n* [[avant-garde metal]]\n* [[black metal]]\n* [[doom metal]]\n* [[drone metal]]\n* [[industrial metal]]\n* [[progressive metal]]\n* [[shoegazing]]\n* [[sludge metal]]\n}}\n\n'''Post-metal''' is a style of music that is rooted in [[heavy metal music|heavy metal]] but explores approaches beyond the genre's conventions. It emerged in the 1990s through the work of bands such as [[Neurosis (band)|Neurosis]] and [[Godflesh]] who transformed metal [[texture (music)|texture]] through [[experimental music|experimental]] composition. Associated with and inspired by [[post-rock]] and [[post-hardcore]], the genre employs the darkness and intensity of [[extreme metal]] but emphasizes atmosphere, emotion, and even \"[[revelation]]\", drawing on a wide range of sources including [[ambient music|ambient]], [[noise music|noise]], [[psychedelic music|psychedelic]], [[progressive music|progressive]], and [[classical music]] to develop an expansive but introspective sound. Post-metal songs are typically long, with loose and layered structures that discard the [[verse\u2013chorus form]] in favor of [[crescendo]]s and repeating [[Theme (music)|theme]]s. The sound centres on guitars and drums; any vocals are usually [[screaming (music)|screamed]] or [[death growl|growled]] and resemble an additional instrument.\n\nPost-metal is closely related to [[avant-garde metal]] and has also been associated with [[sludge metal]], [[drone metal]], [[progressive metal]], and [[industrial metal]]. Alternative names that have been used to describe the genre include '''art metal'''<ref name=\"nyt\" /> and '''metalgaze''',<ref name=\"earles\">{{cite book|last1=Earles|first1=Andrew|title=Gimme Indie Rock|date=2014|publisher=Voyageur|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=D_eKBAAAQBAJ&pg=PA145&lpg=PA145&dq=%22metal-gaze%22+%22post-metal%22&source=bl&ots=pi5if_RwpI&sig=0C13pCbVNJGIIPlgqvoVYB_3Kyk&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwj8nuil6KPMAhWG6xoKHf1jACs4ChDoAQgbMAA#v=onepage&q=%22metal-gaze%22%20%22post-metal%22&f=false|accessdate=15 July 2016}}</ref> highlighting its connection to [[art music]] and [[shoegazing]], respectively. Contemporary post-metal, pioneered by disparate groups such as [[Isis (band)|Isis]], [[Agalloch]], [[Boris (band)|Boris]], [[Pelican (band)|Pelican]], [[Jesu (band)|Jesu]], and [[Wolves in the Throne Room]], often employs the extreme heaviness of [[doom metal]] but has also become associated with shoegazing and [[black metal]]. In particular, the recent critical acclaim of [[Deafheaven]], whose fusion of these two genres has been nicknamed [[blackgaze]], demonstrates the growing success of the global post-metal underground.\n\n==History==\n[[File:Buzz Osborne of The Melvins Live @ Slim's 01.jpg|thumb|right|The [[Melvins]]' combination of [[doom metal]], [[hardcore punk]], and [[avant-garde music|avant-garde]] approaches has been a key influence on post-metal bands.]]\n\n===Predecessors===\nThe groundwork for post-metal was laid in the 1980s and early 1990s by various artists combining [[heavy metal music|heavy metal]] and [[punk rock]] sounds with an \"[[avant-garde music|avant-garde]] sensibility\", such as the [[Melvins]] (particularly on 1991's [[Bullhead (album)|''Bullhead'']]),<ref name=\"bandcamp\">{{cite web|url=https://daily.bandcamp.com/2016/08/04/a-brief-history-of-post-metal/|title=A Brief History of Post-Metal|publisher=Bandcamp|first=Jon|last=Wiederhorn|date=4 August 2016|accessdate=14 November 2017}}</ref> [[the Flying Luttenbachers]], [[Justin Broadrick]] of [[Napalm Death]] and [[Godflesh]],<ref name=\"nyt\" /> [[Swans (band)|Swans]], [[Gore (band)|Gore]], [[Last Exit (free jazz band)|Last Exit]], [[Glenn Branca]], [[Rollins Band]], and [[Fugazi]].<ref name=\"fact\" /> [[Helmet (band)|Helmet]]'s albums [[Meantime (album)|''Meantime'']] (1992) and [[Betty (Helmet album)|''Betty'']] (1994) were also significant,<ref name=\"earles\" /> while [[Tool (band)|Tool]]'s music was described as post-metal as early as 1993.<ref name=\"santiago\">{{cite news | url = http://nl.newsbank.com/nl-search/we/Archives?p_product=ST&s_site=dfw&p_multi=ST&p_theme=realcities&p_action=search&p_maxdocs=200&p_topdoc=1&p_text_direct-0=0EAF8F12C40B57C7&p_field_direct-0=document_id&p_perpage=10&p_sort=YMD_date:D | title = At the main stage ...| first = Dave | last = Ferman | publisher = [[Fort Worth Star-Telegram]], archived by NewsBank | date = 1993-07-30 | accessdate = 2007-05-09 | format = fee required | quote = Tool's vicious, post-metal attack is one of the more intense offerings of the day ...}}</ref> Many of these artists emerged from [[hardcore punk]] and [[post-punk]] circles but their combination of sonic violence with experimentation and [[eclecticism]] made them difficult to categorize under any one genre.<ref name=\"nyt\" />\n\n===Emergence in the 1990s===\nThe term [[post-rock]] was coined in 1994 and soon used to describe a diverse group of bands that shared \"a penchant for drifting melodies and the desire to expand beyond established [[rock music|rock]] boundaries\".<ref name=\"bandcamp\"/> As this movement swelled, bands from [[post-hardcore]] and [[experimental music|experimental]] backgrounds began to incorporate its tendencies of \"[[ambient music|ambience]], offbeat experimentation, downcast melodies and [[psychedelic music|psychedelia]]\" into metal.<ref name=\"bandcamp\"/> The two genres further converged through the influence of post-rock bands such as [[Mogwai]], [[Godspeed You! Black Emperor]], and [[Lift to Experience]] who shared metal's emphasis on loudness.<ref name=\"fact\" />\n\n[[File:Neurosis 038.jpg|thumb|right|[[Neurosis (band)|Neurosis]] have been credited with inventing the genre through their [[experimental music|experimental]], spiritually intense work.]]\n[[Neurosis (band)|Neurosis]]' third album ''[[Souls at Zero]]'' and Godflesh's sophomore album [[Pure (Godflesh album)|''Pure'']], both released in 1992, are often retrospectively considered the first post-metal records.<ref name=\"bandcamp\"/> Godflesh had already pioneered \"sluggish and tortured\" [[industrial metal]] of their 1989 debut [[Streetcleaner (album)|''Streetcleaner'']], but ''Pure'' showcased \"more expansive structures and long stretches of billowing [[noise music|noise]]\", inspiring a number of subsequent bands to combine metal with \"layered washes of sound\".<ref name=\"bandcamp\"/> Neurosis on the other hand were a hardcore band who embraced [[doom metal]], post-punk and [[industrial music|industrial]] influences, experimenting with [[Texture (music)|texture]] and [[Dynamics (music)|dynamics]].<ref name=\"bandcamp\"/> They have since become \"worshipped for their pioneering post-metal efforts and unwavering dedication to expanding their artistic boundaries.\"<ref>{{cite web|last=Mikkelson |first=Jill |url=http://exclaim.ca/Interviews/FromTheMagazine/neurosis_are_insulated |title=Neurosis Are Insulated \u2022 Interviews |publisher=Exclaim.ca |accessdate=2013-01-10}}</ref> In 2010, guitarist [[Steve Von Till]] stated:<ref name=\"gn\">{{cite news|title=How Neurosis blazed a trail for 'thinking man's metal' and lasted 25 years|url=https://www.theguardian.com/music/2010/dec/02/neurosis-live-at-roadburn|last=Thomson|first=Jamie|newspaper=[[The Guardian]]|date=December 2, 2010|accessdate=January 5, 2017}}</ref>\n\n{{quote|We always knew there was something deep to Neurosis's music, but ... I think ''Souls at Zero'' was when the music became something else. It was taking that material out on the road and losing ourself in the [[trance]] states induced by playing [[hypnotic]], super-heavy loud music that we really figured out how to surrender to it. Then we said, OK \u2013 this is going to take us to where we wanna go: somewhere deeper, somewhere more emotional, somewhere [[elemental]].}}\n\nThe band's 1996 fifth album ''[[Through Silver in Blood]]'' was credited by ''[[Terrorizer Magazine|Terrorizer]]'' with \"effectively invent[ing] the post-metal genre\"<ref>Jim Martin, \"Retroaction,\" ''Terrorizer'' #188, September 2009, p. 80.</ref> and named the best post-metal album of all time by [[Fact (UK magazine)|''Fact'']].<ref name=\"fact\" /> The fluctuating 12-minute song \"Purify\" has been described as the album's \"signature track\".<ref name=\"bandcamp\"/> Neurosis' work has also contributed the development of doom metal, [[sludge metal]], and [[drone metal]], and these genres have been associated with post-metal since.<ref name=\"steff\">{{cite web|url=http://www.steffmetal.com/so-just-what-exactly-is-post-metal-anyway/|title=So Just What Exactly Is \"Post Metal\" Anyway?\"|last=Green|first=Steff|publisher=Steff Metal|date=February 9, 2015|accessdate=November 11, 2017}}</ref> Similarly, drone metal pioneers [[Earth (American band)|Earth]] have been significant to post-metal ever since their 1991 debut release ''[[Extra-Capsular Extraction]]''.<ref name=\"bandcamp\"/>\n\n[[File:Aaron T (4775767148).jpg|thumb|left|upright|[[Aaron Turner]] of [[Isis (band)|Isis]] and [[Hydra Head Records]] has been a major figure.]]\nFurthermore, ''Fact'' writer Robin Jahdi highlights the late 1990s [[noisecore]] of bands such as [[Botch (band)|Botch]], [[Kiss It Goodbye]], [[the Dillinger Escape Plan]] and [[Coalesce (band)|Coalesce]], who merged brutal [[metallic hardcore]] with [[jazz]] into fast-and-complex compositions, as a fundamental influence on post-metal.<ref name=\"fact\" /> Writing for ''[[Bandcamp Daily]]'', Jon Wiederhorn also noted the significance of Botch and [[Cave In]],<ref name=\"bandcamp\"/> while [[Converge (band)|Converge]] have been connected to post-metal through their longer songs since the closing track of their seminal 2001 album ''[[Jane Doe (album)|Jane Doe]]''.<ref name=\"convergesucks\">{{cite web|url=http://www.metalsucks.net/2009/06/30/5-converge-jane-doe/|title=21 Best Metal Albums of the 21st Century ... So Far |last=O'Hagar|first=Sammy|publisher=MetalSucks|date=June 30, 2009|accessdate=November 26, 2011}}</ref> According to Jahdi, the genre emerged as \"those young intellectuals decided to slow it down\" and labels such as [[Relapse Records]] and [[Hydra Head Records]] began releasing \"slower, more bass-heavy and abstract\" music more akin to post-rock.<ref name=\"fact\" />\n\n===Development in the 2000s===\nHydra Head Records had been established in 1993 by [[Aaron Turner]]. In 1997, Turner co-founded [[Isis (band)|Isis]], a band which became central to an increasingly recognizable post-metal movement. In particular, their 2002 sophomore album ''[[Oceanic (Isis album)|Oceanic]]'' \u2013 which showcased \"buzzing washes of multilayered sound that ebbed and flowed in intensity\", combining the \"barbed guitars\" and \"[[shouted vocals]]\" of post-hardcore with \"meandering, psychedelic progressions\"<ref name=\"bandcamp\"/> \u2013 has become regarded as a classic of the genre.<ref name=\"fact\" /> At the same time, Hydra Head signed further prominent bands, releasing the early records of [[Pelican (band)|Pelican]] and [[Jesu (band)|Jesu]].<ref name=\"nyt\" /> While Pelican are an [[instrumental music|instrumental]] quartet inspired as much by Neurosis and Godflesh as by Mogwai, Jesu was formed by Justin Broadrick after the breakup of Godflesh to explore \"ambient guitar compositions\", embracing [[shoegazing]] and [[slowcore]] influences.<ref name=\"bandcamp\"/>\n\nAlongside shoegazing, [[black metal]] began to transform post-metal as it \"spread beyond Scandinavia to infect the global underground\".<ref name=\"bandcamp\"/> Many bands employ the \"speed and ferocity\" of black metal in \"contrast to slower, more ethereal compositions\". This approach was pioneered by [[Agalloch]], who formed in 1995 and also employed elements of doom metal, [[progressive rock]], [[folk music]], and post-hardcore.<ref name=\"bandcamp\"/> [[Wolves in the Throne Room]], who became a significant act for American black metal by the release of their 2007 sophomore album ''[[Two Hunters]]'', were also inspired by Neurosis in combining \"ambience and violence\" to craft deeply melancholic music.<ref name=\"bandcamp\"/>\n\nWhile all post-metal pioneers except Broadrick are American, the genre soon spread internationally. In particular, the Japanese band [[Boris (band)|Boris]], formed in 1992, \"have always embraced the spirit and vitality of the vibrant movement\" and some of their works, such as the 2005 albums ''[[Dronevil]]'' and ''[[Pink (Boris album)|Pink]]'', have become influential to it.<ref name=\"bandcamp\"/> Boris often employ elements of [[drone music]] and have collaborated with prominent drone metal band [[Sunn O)))]],<ref name=\"bandcamp\"/> who have also been associated with post-metal.<ref name=\"nyt\" /> Several European bands also gained prominence within the genre, including [[Cult of Luna]] from Sweden, whose sound is indebted to Isis' ''Oceanic'',<ref name=\"steff\" /> [[Amenra]] from Belgium, who signed to Neurosis' label [[Neurot Recordings]] and rival their predecessors in sheer spiritual intensity,<ref name=\"amenra\">{{cite news|url=https://www.independent.co.uk/arts-entertainment/music/features/amenra-mass-vi-album-stream-a8002161.html|title=AMENRA \u2013 MASS VI: Album Stream|last=Dedman|first=Remfry|newspaper=The Independent|date=16 October 2017|accessdate=16 October 2017}}</ref> and [[Year of No Light]] from France, who have transitioned from a sludge-oriented sound to monumental instrumental compositions, \"beautifully layered, but still dark and heavy\".<ref name=\"bandcamp\"/>\n\nAnother prominent instrumental band, [[Russian Circles]], was also strongly influenced by ''Oceanic''.<ref name=\"steff\" /> By contrast, [[True Widow]], whose sound is rooted as much in 1990s [[indie rock]] and [[psychedelic rock]] as in doom metal, offer a distinctive take on post-metal, most impactfully on the 2013's ''[[Circumambulation (album)|Circumambulation]]'', by employing \"male/female vocal interplay\" and showcasing \"vulnerability and restraint\".<ref name=\"bandcamp\"/> Meanwhile, the Melvins had made a direct mark on the sound they themselves inspired with the 2004 album ''[[Pigs of the Roman Empire]]'', a collaboration with [[dark ambient]] composer [[Lustmord]].<ref name=\"bandcamp\"/>\n\nGradually, post-metal as a genre has achieved major critical acclaim.<ref name=\"steff\" /> This was reinforced by the \"widely publicized\" success of [[Deafheaven]],<ref name=\"bandcamp\"/> whose sophomore album ''[[Sunbather (album)|Sunbather]]'' became one of the most celebrated releases of 2013. The band's successful fusion of caustic black metal with blissfull shoegazing in the vein of [[My Bloody Valentine (band)|My Bloody Valentine]] and [[Slowdive]],<ref name=\"bandcamp\"/> though preceded by the French musician [[Neige (musician)|Neige]] of [[Alcest]], was nicknamed [[blackgaze]] and met with disdain from fans of conventional [[extreme metal]]. It has also inspired a wave of bands such as [[Ghost Bath]], who often use undistorted guitar melodies to develop unsettling atmospheres, and Austria's [[Harakiri for the Sky]], whose despairing sound melds black metal and post-hardcore.<ref name=\"bandcamp\"/>\n\n[[File:Deafheaven @ A Colossal Weekend 2017 46.jpg|thumb|right|[[Deafheaven]] have brought the genre widespread critical acclaim in their fusion of [[black metal]] and [[shoegazing]].]]\n\n==Characteristics==\nPost-metal is generally heavy, aggressive, and dark, but explores a variety of musical approaches alien to conventional [[heavy metal music|heavy metal]] and [[extreme metal]].<ref name=\"bandcamp\"/> It mirrors [[post-rock]] and [[post-hardcore]] in its emphasis on atmosphere and deep emotion and may be considered abstract,<ref name=\"fact\" /> introspective,<ref name=\"steff\" /> expansive,<ref name=\"bbc1\">{{cite web | url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/music/reviews/zhj9 | title=Neurosis - Times of Grace Review | publisher=[[BBC]] | accessdate=January 5, 2016 | author=Moffitt, Greg}}</ref> [[hypnotic]],<ref name=\"gn\" /> [[progressive music|progressive]],<ref name=\"bbc1\" /> layered,<ref name=\"bandcamp\"/> or even [[Apocalypse|apocalyptic]].<ref name=\"bbc1\" /> Jon Wiederhorn writes that though some post-metal bands \"sought to break away from their raging roots by exploring less bombastic and more dynamic musical techniques\" and others \"sought to remain raw and corrosive\", their music shares a \"heavy-lidded yet eye-opening\" effect.<ref name=\"bandcamp\"/> ''[[The New York Times]]'' associated the term with a \"wave of bands using metal as a jumping-off point for a range of [[experimental music|experimental]] styles, dabbling in [[free jazz]], [[minimal music|minimalist]] post-rock, [[noise music|noise]] and even [[modern classical music]].\"<ref name=\"nyt\">{{cite news | last = Caraminica | first = Jon | url = https://www.nytimes.com/2005/09/20/arts/the-alchemy-of-artworld-heavy-metal.html | title = The alchemy of art-world heavy metal | newspaper = [[The New York Times]] | accessdate = 2005-09-20}}</ref> Contemporary post-metal bands incorporate influences ranging through [[doom metal]], [[black metal]], [[shoegazing]], [[progressive rock]], [[folk music]], and [[classical music]].<ref name=\"bandcamp\"/>\n\nWriting for [[Slate (magazine)|''Slate'']] in 2009, [[Simon Reynolds]] reflected:\n{{quote|[P]ost-rock doesn't have the same temporal aspect that [[post-disco]] or [[post-punk]] have; it's not about the ripples set in motion by a galvanizing \"event.\" Rather, it evokes a sense of \"going beyond\" the structures of a genre of music without completely abandoning its legacy of attitudes and assumptions. For similar reasons, the term post-metal seems increasingly useful to describe the vast and variegated swath of genres (the thousand flavors of doom/black/[[death metal|death]]/[[grindcore|grind]]/[[drone metal|drone]]/[[sludge metal|sludge]]/etc., ad infinitum) that emerged from the early '90s onward. Sometimes beat-free and [[ambient music|ambient]], increasingly the work of home-studio loners rather than performing bands, post-metal of the kind released by labels like [[Hydra Head Records|Hydra Head]] often seems to have barely any connection to metal as understood by, say, [[VH1 Classic]] doc-makers. The continuity is less sonic but attitudinal: the penchant for [[Fascination with death|morbidity]] and darkness taken to a sometimes hokey degree; the somber clothing and the long hair; the harrowed, indecipherably [[growled vocals]]; the bombastically verbose lyrics/song titles/band names. It's that aesthetic rather than a way of riffing or a palette of guitar sounds that ties post-metal back to [[Judas Priest]] and [[Black Sabbath]].<ref>{{cite web|title=Grunge's Long Shadow|url=http://www.slate.com/articles/arts/music_box/2009/05/grunges_long_shadow.single.html#pagebreak_anchor_2|accessdate=2010-11-14|authorlink=Simon Reynolds|work=[[Slate (magazine)|Slate]]}}</ref>}}\n\n[[File:Russian Circles - Madrid - 15 abril 2015 2.JPG|thumb|left|Many groups, including [[Russian Circles]], are [[instrumental]].]]\nPost-metal is therefore notoriously difficult to define.{{original research inline|date=September 2018}} ''[[Fact (UK magazine)|Fact]]'' writer Robin Jahdi notes that \"the best [[Neurosis (band)|Neurosis]] albums don't sound anything like the best offerings from [[Isis (band)|Isis]]\" and that the genre cannot be readily distinguished from doom metal, modern black metal, and [[progressive metal]], \"[taking] in all of these elements without being entirely any one of them\".<ref name=\"fact\">{{cite web | url=http://www.factmag.com/2015/06/24/40-best-post-metal/ | title=The 40 best post-metal records ever made | work=[[Fact (UK magazine)|Fact]] | date=June 24, 2015 | accessdate=November 11, 2017 | author=Jahdi, Robin}}</ref> Contemporary post-metal is often seen as combining \"elements of doom metal, sludge, and/or black metal with elements of post-rock and shoegaze\", being more \"peaceful\" than metal but retaining its dark theming and [[screaming (music)|harsh vocal style]].<ref name=\"steff\" /> As with post-rock, however, many bands are [[instrumental]] and when vocals are used, they often \"resemble [another] accompanying instrument\" rather than actual words.<ref name=\"steff\" /> Songs are typically long and employ [[crescendo]]s, gradually building upon repeated [[Theme (music)|theme]]s; [[Aaron Turner]] of Isis stated that \"the standard song format of [[Verse\u2013chorus form|verse-chorus-verse-chorus]] is something that has been done and redone, and it seems pointless to adhere to that structure when there are so many other avenues to explore\".<ref name=\"isisguitar\">{{cite magazine\n| last = Porosky | first = Pamela | url = http://www.guitarplayer.com/story.asp?storyCode=78 | archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20160304072104/http://www.guitarplayer.com/story.asp?storyCode=78 | url-status = dead | archive-date = 2016-03-04 | title = Aaron Turner and Michael Gallagher interview | magazine = [[Guitar Player]] | accessdate = 2006-09-06}} {{dead link|date=November 2017}}</ref>\n\n===Aesthetic and culture===\nWhile Simon Reynolds locates the connection between post-metal and conventional metal in attitude and aesthetic over musical approach, others have emphasized differences in these very areas.{{failed verification|date=September 2018}} Noting the divergence from typical [[metal fashion]], ''[[The New York Times]]'' described a 2005 [[Pelican (band)|Pelican]] show at the [[Knitting Factory]] in [[New York City]]: \"Instead of long hair and all-black outfits, the crowd was displaying the trappings of brainy, slightly nerdy [[indie rock]]. Young men wore artistically cropped hair and [[Slim-fit pants|tight-legged jeans]], and there was even a smattering of young women in librarian glasses and worn-out [[Chuck Taylor All-Stars|Chuck Taylor]] sneakers.\"<ref name=\"nyt\" /> Jon Wiederhorn describes the post-metal scene as a \"global community of artists\" positioned on the \"fringes of the [[underground music|underground]].\"<ref name=\"bandcamp\"/> Pelican's Trevor de Brauw stated in 2007:<ref>{{cite web | url = http://www.drownedinsound.com/articles/1801290 | title = Pelican: \"We're neither trend setters nor trend followers\" | first = Mike | last = Diver | work = [[Drowned in Sound]] | date = 2007-03-27 | accessdate = 2007-03-29}}</ref>\n\n[[File:Pelican performing at Sant Feliu Fest 2004.jpg|thumb|[[Pelican (band)|Pelican]], also instrumental, diverge from [[heavy metal music|heavy metal]] conventions in all aspects of their style and approach.]]\n{{quote|I have an affinity [f]or metal, but I don't think of Pelican as a metal band. So when people call us 'instrumetal', or post-metal, or [[metalcore]] or whatever, I can see why they say that, but it's not something that I feel a close connection with. I feel we're part of a community with some bands \u2013 [[Mono (Japanese band)|Mono]] are good friends of ours, but I don't feel that we're that similar musically. Their music is more similar to classical music, whereas I feel ours has more in common with [[punk rock|punk]] and [[hardcore punk|hardcore]].|sign=|source=}}\n\n==List of bands==\n{{columns-list|colwidth=15em|\n\n'''A'''\n* [[A Hope for Home]]<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.absolutepunk.net/showthread.php?t=1618762|title=chorus.fm|website=chorus.fm}}</ref>\n* [[Agalloch]]<ref name=\"bandcamp\"/>\n* [[Alcest]]<ref>{{cite magazine | url=https://www.rollingstone.com/music/pictures/10-new-artists-you-need-to-know-january-2014-20140124/alcest-0034319 | title=Alcest | magazine=[[Rolling Stone]] | accessdate=15 April 2015 | author=Grow, Kory}}</ref><ref name=\"CoS\">{{Cite news|url=http://consequenceofsound.net/2016/11/the-top-10-metal-albums-of-2016/full-post/|title=The Top 10 Metal Albums of 2016|last1=Barry|first1=Sean|first2=Jon|last2=Hadusek|newspaper=Consequence of Sound|access-date=December 17, 2016}}</ref>\n* [[Altar of Plagues]]<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.allmusic.com/artist/altar-of-plagues-mn0001060698 |title=Altar of Plagues |first=Gregory |last=Heaney |publisher=[[AllMusic]] |accessdate=February 4, 2013 |archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/6EBeWmgWr?url=http://www.allmusic.com/artist/altar-of-plagues-mn0001060698 |archivedate=4 February 2013 |url-status=live }}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://heavymetal.about.com/od/altarofplagues/fr/Altar-Of-Plagues-Mammal-Review.htm |title=Altar Of Plagues \u2013 Mammal |first=Marcus |last=Jervis |publisher=[[About.com]] |accessdate=February 4, 2013 |archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/6EBeprhXl?url=http://heavymetal.about.com/od/altarofplagues/fr/Altar-Of-Plagues-Mammal-Review.htm |archivedate=2013-02-04 |url-status=dead }}</ref><ref>{{cite magazine|url=http://www.popmatters.com/pm/review/142177-altar-of-plagues-mammal/ |title=Altar of Plagues: Mammal |first=Adrien |last=Begrand |date=June 21, 2011 |magazine=[[PopMatters]] |accessdate=February 4, 2013 |archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/6EBfQhz6N?url=http://www.popmatters.com/pm/review/142177-altar-of-plagues-mammal/ |archivedate=4 February 2013 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n* [[Amenra]]<ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.brusselnieuws.be/nl/nieuws/etherische-postmetal-van-amenra-klinkt-als-pletwals | title=Etherische postmetal van Amenra klinkt als pletwals | publisher=Brussel Deze Week | work=Agenda Magazine | date=12 December 2012 | accessdate=20 November 2014 | author=Peeters, Tom|language=Dutch}}</ref>\n* [[Amesoeurs]]<ref>Azevedo, Pedro. [http://www.chroniclesofchaos.com/reviews/albums/2-6116_les_discrets_septembre_et_ses_derni\u00e8res_pens\u00e9es.aspx \"Les Discrets \u2013 Septembre et Ses Derni\u00e8res Pens\u00e9es\"]. Chronicles of Chaos. Retrieved 29 December 2011.</ref>\n* [[Ancestors (band)|Ancestors]]<ref>{{cite news|last=Roche|first=Jason|title=Exclusive Track: Ancestors' New Song 'Whispers'|url=http://blogs.laweekly.com/westcoastsound/2012/04/exclusive_track_ancestors_new.php|accessdate=19 April 2012|newspaper=[[LA Weekly]]|publisher=[[Village Voice Media]]|date=2 April 2012}}</ref>\n* [[Archivist (band)|Archivist]]<ref name=\"EnD\">{{cite web|url=https://www.echoesanddust.com/2017/04/archivist-construct/|title=Archivist \u2013 ''Construct''|last=Butler|first=Matt|publisher=Echoes and Dust|date=30 April 2017|accessdate=1 March 2019}}</ref>\n* [[Astronoid]]<ref>{{cite web |last1=Nelson |first1=Michael |title=Band To Watch: Astronoid |url=https://www.stereogum.com/1880105/band-to-watch-astronoid/franchises/band-to-watch/ |website=Stereogum |accessdate=10 November 2018}}</ref>\n\n'''B'''\n* [[Battle of Mice]]<ref>True, Chris. [http://www.allmusic.com/artist/battle-of-mice-p783686 \"Battle of Mice\"]. [[AllMusic]]. Retrieved 27 November 2011.</ref>\n* [[The Black Heart Rebellion]]<ref name=\"fmz\">{{cite web|url=http://www.fullmoonzine.cz/novinky/the-black-heart-rebellion-se-vraci|title=The Black Heart Rebellion se vrac\u00ed|trans-title=The Black Heart Rebellion return|language=Czech|publisher=Full Moon|date=7 January 2019|accessdate=5 March 2019}}</ref>\n* [[Boris (band)|Boris]]<ref name=\"nyt1\">{{cite news | last = Caraminica | first = Jon | url = http://www.iht.com/articles/2005/09/19/features/heavy.php | title = The alchemy of art-world heavy metal | newspaper = [[The New York Times]] | accessdate = 20 September 2005}}</ref>\n* [[Burst (band)|Burst]]<ref name=\"burst\">{{cite magazine | first = Aaron | last = Burgess | url = http://altpress.com/reviews/173.htm | title = The loveliest album to crush our skull in months | magazine = [[Alternative Press (music magazine)|Alternative Press]] | accessdate = 29 January 2008 | date = 23 May 2006 | archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20110809212036/http://www.altpress.com/reviews/173.htm | archive-date = 2011-08-09 | url-status = dead }}</ref>\n\n'''C'''\n* [[Callisto (band)|Callisto]]<ref>{{cite web|title=Provinssirockin lauantain p\u00e4\u00e4esiintyj\u00e4ksi Manowar (US)|url=http://www.festivals.fi/uutiset/123/|publisher=Finland Festivals|accessdate=29 November 2011|language=Finnish|date=5 June 2009|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20111007233009/http://www.festivals.fi/uutiset/123/|archive-date=2011-10-07|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n* [[Cult of Luna]]<ref name=\"burst\"/>\n\n'''D'''\n* [[Deafheaven]]<ref name=\"bandcamp\"/>\n* [[Deftones]]\n* [[Dirge (band)|Dirge]]<ref>True, Chris. [{{AllMusic|class=artist|id=p984201/biography|pure_url=yes}} \"Dirge\"]. AllMusic. Retrieved 29 December 2011.</ref>\n* [[Downfall of Gaia]]<ref>{{cite web|title=Downfall of Gaia: \"''Aeon Unveils the Thrones of Decay''\"|url=http://www.nocleansinging.com/2014/12/04/downfall-of-gaia-aeon-unveils-the-thrones-of-decay/|last=Weber|first=Austin|publisher=[[No Clean Singing]]|date=4 December 2014|accessdate=20 October 2016|quote=}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=Interview: Downfall of Gaia|url=http://echoesanddust.com/2014/12/interview-downfall-of-gaia/|last=Rawlinson|first=Andrew|publisher=[[Echoes and Dust]]|date=30 December 2014|accessdate=20 October 2016|quote=}}</ref>\n\n'''E'''\n* [[Earth (American band)|Earth]]<ref name=\"bandcamp\"/>\n\n'''G'''\n* [[Ghost Bath]]<ref name=\"bandcamp\"/>\n* [[Godflesh]]<ref name=\"bandcamp\"/>\n\n'''H'''\n* [[Harakiri for the Sky]]<ref name=\"bandcamp\"/>\n* [[Heaven in Her Arms]]<ref>{{cite web|url=https://pitchfork.com/reviews/albums/heaven-in-her-arms-white-halo/|title=Heaven in Her Arms: ''White Halo''|last=O'Connor|first=Andy|website=Pitchfork|date=10 July 2017|accessdate=27 December 2017}}</ref>\n\n'''I'''\n* [[Intronaut]]<ref>{{cite web|url=http://exclaim.ca/Reviews/Metal/Intronaut-Valley_Of_Smoke|title=Valley of Smoke review|last=Carman|first=Keith|date=November 2010|work=[[Exclaim!]]|accessdate=10 August 2011|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20101216073704/http://exclaim.ca/Reviews/Metal/Intronaut-Valley_Of_Smoke#|archive-date=2010-12-16|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n* [[Isis (band)|Isis]]<ref>{{cite web|url=http://heavymetal.about.com/od/cdreviews/fr/isisintheabsenc.htm|title=Reviews|publisher=}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |url=http://altpress.com/reviews/430.htm |title=''In the Absence of Truth'' review at Altpress |access-date=2007-08-02 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110809210810/http://www.altpress.com/reviews/430.htm |archive-date=2011-08-09 |url-status=dead }}</ref><ref name=\"bandcamp\"/>\n\n'''J'''\n* [[Jesu (band)|Jesu]]<ref>{{cite web|last=Jurek|first=Thom|title=Heart Ache/Dethroned \u2013 Jesu|url=http://www.allmusic.com/album/heart-achedethroned-r2049023/review|publisher=[[Allmusic]]|accessdate=29 December 2011}}</ref><ref name=\"bandcamp\"/>\n*[[Junius (band)|Junius]]<ref>Geist, Brandon. [https://www.rollingstone.com/music/premieres/hear-junius-crushing-new-post-metal-epic-w463118 \"Junius \u2013 The Queen's Constellation\"]. Rolling Stone. Retrieved 27 January 2017.</ref>\n\n'''M'''\n* [[Made Out of Babies]]<ref>True, Chris. [http://www.allmusic.com/artist/made-out-of-babies-p724740 \"Made Out of Babies biography\"]. [[Allmusic]]. Retrieved 27 November 2011.</ref><ref>[http://www.skinnymag.co.uk/content/view/3061/141/ Review of ''Red Sparowes / Made Out of Babies / Battle of Mice''] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20071213233107/http://www.skinnymag.co.uk/content/view/3061/141/ |date=13 December 2007 }}</ref><ref>[http://www.deafsparrow.com/Made-Out-ofBabies-review.htm \"Made Out of Babies \u2013 The Ruiner review \u2013 Deaf Sparrow Zine\"] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120614182931/http://www.deafsparrow.com/Made-Out-ofBabies-review.htm |date=14 June 2012 }}. deafsparrow.com. Retrieved 1 December 2011.</ref>\n* [[Melvins]]<ref name=\"bandcamp\"/>\n* [[Mouth of the Architect]]<ref>[{{AllMusic|class=album|id=r849391|pure_url=yes}} ''The Ties That Blind'' review at AllMusic]</ref>\n\n'''N'''\n* [[Neurosis (band)|Neurosis]]<ref name=\"bandcamp\"/>\n* [[Nadja (band)|Nadja]]<ref>True, Chris. [http://www.allmusic.com/artist/nadja-p741872 \"Nadja\"]. [[AllMusic]]. Retrieved 28 November 2011.</ref>\n\n'''O'''\n* [[Oathbreaker (band)|Oathbreaker]]<ref name=\"CoS\" />\n* [[The Ocean (band)|The Ocean]]<ref>{{cite web|url={{Allmusic|class=album|id=fluxion-r907618/review|pure_url=yes}}|title=Review of Fluxion|last=Freeman|first=Phil|work=[[AllMusic]]|accessdate=14 November 2010|quote=The Ocean, a largely Berlin-based musical collective, occupy a space right near Neurosis, Isis, and Cult of Luna in the post-metal arena.}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.avclub.com/articles/april-2010,40102/|title=At the Post|last=Pierce|first=Leonard|date=14 April 2010|work=[[The A.V. Club]]|accessdate=14 November 2010}}</ref>\n\n'''P'''\n* [[Pelican (band)|Pelican]]<ref>Jurek, Thom. [http://www.allmusic.com/album/what-we-all-come-to-need-r1663003/review \"Allmusic review: Pelican \u2013 What We All Come to Need\"]. [[AllMusic]]. Retrieved 27 November 2011.</ref><ref name=\"canoe\">{{cite news | url = http://jam.canoe.ca/Music/2006/06/14/1631268.html | archive-url = https://archive.is/20120709090408/http://jam.canoe.ca/Music/2006/06/14/1631268.html | url-status = dead | archive-date = 9 July 2012 | title = Pelican's music tough to categorize | first = Allan | last = Wigley | newspaper = [[Ottawa Sun]] | date = 14 June 2006 | accessdate = 2 August 2007 }}</ref><ref name=\"bandcamp\"/>\n* [[Prong (band)|Prong]]<ref>{{cite web|last=Ramirez|first=Carlos|title=Prong Keep Things Lean and Mean on 'Ammunition' \u2013 Song Premiere|url=http://www.noisecreep.com/2012/04/11/prong-ammunition-song/|work=[[Noisecreep]]|publisher=[[AOL]]|accessdate=19 April 2012|date=11 April 2012}}</ref>\n* [[Palms (band)|Palms]]<ref>Weingarten, Christopher R. [http://www.spin.com/2013/06/stream-palms-debut-chino-moreno-isis-deftones/]. [[Spin (magazine)|Spin]] Retrieved 2 October 2015.</ref>\n\n'''R'''\n* [[Russian Circles]]<ref name=\"steff\" />\n* [[Rosetta (band)|Rosetta]]{{citation needed|date=September 2018}}\n\n'''T'''\n* [[Tool (band)|Tool]]<ref name=\"fenix\">{{cite magazine | url = http://www.variety.com/review/VE1117905701.html?categoryid=34&cs=1 | title = Live Performances: Tool | first = Troy J. | last = Augusto | magazine = [[Variety (magazine)|Variety]] | date = 16 October 1996 | accessdate = 9 May 2007 | quote = The group's rhythm section, featuring new bassist Justin Chancellor, propelled the group's post-metal stylings with a twisted, near-jazz approach.}}</ref><ref name=\"bairdcole\">{{cite news | url = http://www.denverpost.com/entertainment/ci_4298028 | title = Reverb, 9/01: Tool | first = Ricardo | last = Baca | newspaper = [[The Denver Post]] | date = 8 September 2006 | accessdate = 9 May 2007 | quote = ... Tool's bag of post-metal goodies, and it's every bit as fear-inducing as it was in 1993.}}</ref>\n* [[True Widow]]<ref name=\"bandcamp\"/>\n\n'''U'''\n* [[Ulcerate]]<ref>{{cite journal|last=Horsley|first=Jonathan|date=March 2011|title=Kiwi death merchants destroy 'em all|journal=[[Decibel (magazine)|Decibel]]|issue=77|pages=32|issn=1557-2137|quote=What could be better than some evocatively bleak [[death metal]] while panic-buying canned goods and bottled water on the day when the chemical factory has turned the sky green and the river purple? New rager ''[[The Destroyers of All]]'' is a disorienting, desolate doozy, taking elements of weird post-metal to construct a sound that would be mother's milk to [[Attention deficit hyperactivity disorder|ADHD]] [[Neurosis (band)|Neurosis]] fans.}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|title=Everything Is Fire review|url=http://www.allmusic.com/album/everything-is-fire-r1508696/review|first=Phil|last=Freeman|accessdate=24 April 2011|work=[[Allmusic]]|quote=Their music combines the brutal, downtuned riffing of traditional death metal (think [[Immolation (band)|Immolation]] or [[Morbid Angel]]) with the dissonance and shifting time signatures of [[Gorguts]] and the slow, atmospheric passages reminiscent of [[Isis (band)|Isis]].}}</ref>\n\n'''W'''\n* [[We Lost the Sea]]{{citation needed|date=November 2019}}\n* [[Wolves in the Throne Room]]<ref name=\"bandcamp\"/>\n\n'''Y'''\n* [[Year of No Light]]<ref>[http://www.allmusic.com/artist/year-of-no-light-mn0000525681/biography]. AllMusic.com</ref><ref name=\"bandcamp\"/>\n}}\n\n==See also==\n*[[Avant-garde metal]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|2}}\n\n{{Heavymetal}}\n{{Experimental music genres}}\n{{Extreme metal}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Post-Metal}}\n[[Category:Post-metal| ]]\n[[Category:Heavy metal genres]]\n[[Category:Experimental music genres]]\n[[Category:Avant-garde metal]]\n[[Category:Experimental rock]]\n[[Category:Post-rock]]\n[[Category:American styles of music]]\n[[Category:American rock music genres]]\n[[Category:English styles of music]]\n[[Category:British rock music genres]]\n", "text_old": "{{Multiple issues|\n{{essay-like|date=September 2018}}\n{{synthesis|article|date=September 2018}}\n}}\n\n{{Infobox music genre\n| name = Post-metal\n| bgcolor = #BB0022\n| color = white\n| other_names = *Art metal\n*metalgaze\n| stylistic_origins = <!-- please do not make unexplained changes -->{{hlist|[[Extreme metal]]|[[experimental music|experimental]]|[[post-rock]]|[[post-hardcore]]}}\n| cultural_origins = 1990s, [[United States]] and [[England]]\n| instruments = {{hlist|[[Electric guitar]]|[[Bass guitar|bass]]|[[Drum kit|drums]]}}\n| derivatives = [[Blackgaze]]\n| regional_scenes = \n| local_scenes = \n| other_topics = * [[Alternative metal]]\n* [[avant-garde metal]]\n* [[black metal]]\n* [[doom metal]]\n* [[drone metal]]\n* [[industrial metal]]\n* [[progressive metal]]\n* [[shoegazing]]\n* [[sludge metal]]\n}}\n\n'''Post-metal''' is a style of music that is rooted in [[heavy metal music|heavy metal]] but explores approaches beyond the genre's conventions. It emerged in the 1990s through the work of bands such as [[Neurosis (band)|Neurosis]] and [[Godflesh]] who transformed metal [[texture (music)|texture]] through [[experimental music|experimental]] composition. Associated with and inspired by [[post-rock]] and [[post-hardcore]], the genre employs the darkness and intensity of [[extreme metal]] but emphasizes atmosphere, emotion, and even \"[[revelation]]\", drawing on a wide range of sources including [[ambient music|ambient]], [[noise music|noise]], [[psychedelic music|psychedelic]], [[progressive music|progressive]], and [[classical music]] to develop an expansive but introspective sound. Post-metal songs are typically long, with loose and layered structures that discard the [[verse\u2013chorus form]] in favor of [[crescendo]]s and repeating [[Theme (music)|theme]]s. The sound centres on guitars and drums; any vocals are usually [[screaming (music)|screamed]] or [[death growl|growled]] and resemble an additional instrument.\n\nPost-metal is closely related to [[avant-garde metal]] and has also been associated with [[sludge metal]], [[drone metal]], [[progressive metal]], and [[industrial metal]]. Alternative names that have been used to describe the genre include '''art metal'''<ref name=\"nyt\" /> and '''metalgaze''',<ref name=\"earles\">{{cite book|last1=Earles|first1=Andrew|title=Gimme Indie Rock|date=2014|publisher=Voyageur|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=D_eKBAAAQBAJ&pg=PA145&lpg=PA145&dq=%22metal-gaze%22+%22post-metal%22&source=bl&ots=pi5if_RwpI&sig=0C13pCbVNJGIIPlgqvoVYB_3Kyk&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwj8nuil6KPMAhWG6xoKHf1jACs4ChDoAQgbMAA#v=onepage&q=%22metal-gaze%22%20%22post-metal%22&f=false|accessdate=15 July 2016}}</ref> highlighting its connection to [[art music]] and [[shoegazing]], respectively. Contemporary post-metal, pioneered by disparate groups such as [[Isis (band)|Isis]], [[Agalloch]], [[Boris (band)|Boris]], [[Pelican (band)|Pelican]], [[Jesu (band)|Jesu]], and [[Wolves in the Throne Room]], often employs the extreme heaviness of [[doom metal]] but has also become associated with shoegazing and [[black metal]]. In particular, the recent critical acclaim of [[Deafheaven]], whose fusion of these two genres has been nicknamed [[blackgaze]], demonstrates the growing success of the global post-metal underground.\n\n==History==\n[[File:Buzz Osborne of The Melvins Live @ Slim's 01.jpg|thumb|right|The [[Melvins]]' combination of [[doom metal]], [[hardcore punk]], and [[avant-garde music|avant-garde]] approaches has been a key influence on post-metal bands.]]\n\n===Predecessors===\nThe groundwork for post-metal was laid in the 1980s and early 1990s by various artists combining [[heavy metal music|heavy metal]] and [[punk rock]] sounds with an \"[[avant-garde music|avant-garde]] sensibility\", such as the [[Melvins]] (particularly on 1991's [[Bullhead (album)|''Bullhead'']]),<ref name=\"bandcamp\">{{cite web|url=https://daily.bandcamp.com/2016/08/04/a-brief-history-of-post-metal/|title=A Brief History of Post-Metal|publisher=Bandcamp|first=Jon|last=Wiederhorn|date=4 August 2016|accessdate=14 November 2017}}</ref> [[the Flying Luttenbachers]], [[Justin Broadrick]] of [[Napalm Death]] and [[Godflesh]],<ref name=\"nyt\" /> [[Swans (band)|Swans]], [[Gore (band)|Gore]], [[Last Exit (free jazz band)|Last Exit]], [[Glenn Branca]], [[Rollins Band]], and [[Fugazi]].<ref name=\"fact\" /> [[Helmet (band)|Helmet]]'s albums [[Meantime (album)|''Meantime'']] (1992) and [[Betty (Helmet album)|''Betty'']] (1994) were also significant,<ref name=\"earles\" /> while [[Tool (band)|Tool]]'s music was described as post-metal as early as 1993.<ref name=\"santiago\">{{cite news | url = http://nl.newsbank.com/nl-search/we/Archives?p_product=ST&s_site=dfw&p_multi=ST&p_theme=realcities&p_action=search&p_maxdocs=200&p_topdoc=1&p_text_direct-0=0EAF8F12C40B57C7&p_field_direct-0=document_id&p_perpage=10&p_sort=YMD_date:D | title = At the main stage ...| first = Dave | last = Ferman | publisher = [[Fort Worth Star-Telegram]], archived by NewsBank | date = 1993-07-30 | accessdate = 2007-05-09 | format = fee required | quote = Tool's vicious, post-metal attack is one of the more intense offerings of the day ...}}</ref> Many of these artists emerged from [[hardcore punk]] and [[post-punk]] circles but their combination of sonic violence with experimentation and [[eclecticism]] made them difficult to categorize under any one genre.<ref name=\"nyt\" />\n\n===Emergence in the 1990s===\nThe term [[post-rock]] was coined in 1994 and soon used to describe a diverse group of bands that shared \"a penchant for drifting melodies and the desire to expand beyond established [[rock music|rock]] boundaries\".<ref name=\"bandcamp\"/> As this movement swelled, bands from [[post-hardcore]] and [[experimental music|experimental]] backgrounds began to incorporate its tendencies of \"[[ambient music|ambience]], offbeat experimentation, downcast melodies and [[psychedelic music|psychedelia]]\" into metal.<ref name=\"bandcamp\"/> The two genres further converged through the influence of post-rock bands such as [[Mogwai]], [[Godspeed You! Black Emperor]], and [[Lift to Experience]] who shared metal's emphasis on loudness.<ref name=\"fact\" />\n\n[[File:Neurosis 038.jpg|thumb|right|[[Neurosis (band)|Neurosis]] have been credited with inventing the genre through their [[experimental music|experimental]], spiritually intense work.]]\n[[Neurosis (band)|Neurosis]]' third album ''[[Souls at Zero]]'' and Godflesh's sophomore album [[Pure (Godflesh album)|''Pure'']], both released in 1992, are often retrospectively considered the first post-metal records.<ref name=\"bandcamp\"/> Godflesh had already pioneered \"sluggish and tortured\" [[industrial metal]] of their 1989 debut [[Streetcleaner (album)|''Streetcleaner'']], but ''Pure'' showcased \"more expansive structures and long stretches of billowing [[noise music|noise]]\", inspiring a number of subsequent bands to combine metal with \"layered washes of sound\".<ref name=\"bandcamp\"/> Neurosis on the other hand were a hardcore band who embraced [[doom metal]], post-punk and [[industrial music|industrial]] influences, experimenting with [[Texture (music)|texture]] and [[Dynamics (music)|dynamics]].<ref name=\"bandcamp\"/> They have since become \"worshipped for their pioneering post-metal efforts and unwavering dedication to expanding their artistic boundaries.\"<ref>{{cite web|last=Mikkelson |first=Jill |url=http://exclaim.ca/Interviews/FromTheMagazine/neurosis_are_insulated |title=Neurosis Are Insulated \u2022 Interviews |publisher=Exclaim.ca |accessdate=2013-01-10}}</ref> In 2010, guitarist [[Steve Von Till]] stated:<ref name=\"gn\">{{cite news|title=How Neurosis blazed a trail for 'thinking man's metal' and lasted 25 years|url=https://www.theguardian.com/music/2010/dec/02/neurosis-live-at-roadburn|last=Thomson|first=Jamie|newspaper=[[The Guardian]]|date=December 2, 2010|accessdate=January 5, 2017}}</ref>\n\n{{quote|We always knew there was something deep to Neurosis's music, but ... I think ''Souls at Zero'' was when the music became something else. It was taking that material out on the road and losing ourself in the [[trance]] states induced by playing [[hypnotic]], super-heavy loud music that we really figured out how to surrender to it. Then we said, OK \u2013 this is going to take us to where we wanna go: somewhere deeper, somewhere more emotional, somewhere [[elemental]].}}\n\nThe band's 1996 fifth album ''[[Through Silver in Blood]]'' was credited by ''[[Terrorizer Magazine|Terrorizer]]'' with \"effectively invent[ing] the post-metal genre\"<ref>Jim Martin, \"Retroaction,\" ''Terrorizer'' #188, September 2009, p. 80.</ref> and named the best post-metal album of all time by [[Fact (UK magazine)|''Fact'']].<ref name=\"fact\" /> The fluctuating 12-minute song \"Purify\" has been described as the album's \"signature track\".<ref name=\"bandcamp\"/> Neurosis' work has also contributed the development of doom metal, [[sludge metal]], and [[drone metal]], and these genres have been associated with post-metal since.<ref name=\"steff\">{{cite web|url=http://www.steffmetal.com/so-just-what-exactly-is-post-metal-anyway/|title=So Just What Exactly Is \"Post Metal\" Anyway?\"|last=Green|first=Steff|publisher=Steff Metal|date=February 9, 2015|accessdate=November 11, 2017}}</ref> Similarly, drone metal pioneers [[Earth (American band)|Earth]] have been significant to post-metal ever since their 1991 debut release ''[[Extra-Capsular Extraction]]''.<ref name=\"bandcamp\"/>\n\n[[File:Aaron T (4775767148).jpg|thumb|left|upright|[[Aaron Turner]] of [[Isis (band)|Isis]] and [[Hydra Head Records]] has been a major figure.]]\nFurthermore, ''Fact'' writer Robin Jahdi highlights the late 1990s [[noisecore]] of bands such as [[Botch (band)|Botch]], [[Kiss It Goodbye]], [[the Dillinger Escape Plan]] and [[Coalesce (band)|Coalesce]], who merged brutal [[metallic hardcore]] with [[jazz]] into fast-and-complex compositions, as a fundamental influence on post-metal.<ref name=\"fact\" /> Writing for ''[[Bandcamp Daily]]'', Jon Wiederhorn also noted the significance of Botch and [[Cave In]],<ref name=\"bandcamp\"/> while [[Converge (band)|Converge]] have been connected to post-metal through their longer songs since the closing track of their seminal 2001 album ''[[Jane Doe (album)|Jane Doe]]''.<ref name=\"convergesucks\">{{cite web|url=http://www.metalsucks.net/2009/06/30/5-converge-jane-doe/|title=21 Best Metal Albums of the 21st Century ... So Far |last=O'Hagar|first=Sammy|publisher=MetalSucks|date=June 30, 2009|accessdate=November 26, 2011}}</ref> According to Jahdi, the genre emerged as \"those young intellectuals decided to slow it down\" and labels such as [[Relapse Records]] and [[Hydra Head Records]] began releasing \"slower, more bass-heavy and abstract\" music more akin to post-rock.<ref name=\"fact\" />\n\n===Development in the 2000s===\nHydra Head Records had been established in 1993 by [[Aaron Turner]]. In 1997, Turner co-founded [[Isis (band)|Isis]], a band which became central to an increasingly recognizable post-metal movement. In particular, their 2002 sophomore album ''[[Oceanic (Isis album)|Oceanic]]'' \u2013 which showcased \"buzzing washes of multilayered sound that ebbed and flowed in intensity\", combining the \"barbed guitars\" and \"[[shouted vocals]]\" of post-hardcore with \"meandering, psychedelic progressions\"<ref name=\"bandcamp\"/> \u2013 has become regarded as a classic of the genre.<ref name=\"fact\" /> At the same time, Hydra Head signed further prominent bands, releasing the early records of [[Pelican (band)|Pelican]] and [[Jesu (band)|Jesu]].<ref name=\"nyt\" /> While Pelican are an [[instrumental music|instrumental]] quartet inspired as much by Neurosis and Godflesh as by Mogwai, Jesu was formed by Justin Broadrick after the breakup of Godflesh to explore \"ambient guitar compositions\", embracing [[shoegazing]] and [[slowcore]] influences.<ref name=\"bandcamp\"/>\n\nAlongside shoegazing, [[black metal]] began to transform post-metal as it \"spread beyond Scandinavia to infect the global underground\".<ref name=\"bandcamp\"/> Many bands employ the \"speed and ferocity\" of black metal in \"contrast to slower, more ethereal compositions\". This approach was pioneered by [[Agalloch]], who formed in 1995 and also employed elements of doom metal, [[progressive rock]], [[folk music]], and post-hardcore.<ref name=\"bandcamp\"/> [[Wolves in the Throne Room]], who became a significant act for American black metal by the release of their 2007 sophomore album ''[[Two Hunters]]'', were also inspired by Neurosis in combining \"ambience and violence\" to craft deeply melancholic music.<ref name=\"bandcamp\"/>\n\nWhile all post-metal pioneers except Broadrick are American, the genre soon spread internationally. In particular, the Japanese band [[Boris (band)|Boris]], formed in 1992, \"have always embraced the spirit and vitality of the vibrant movement\" and some of their works, such as the 2005 albums ''[[Dronevil]]'' and ''[[Pink (Boris album)|Pink]]'', have become influential to it.<ref name=\"bandcamp\"/> Boris often employ elements of [[drone music]] and have collaborated with prominent drone metal band [[Sunn O)))]],<ref name=\"bandcamp\"/> who have also been associated with post-metal.<ref name=\"nyt\" /> Several European bands also gained prominence within the genre, including [[Cult of Luna]] from Sweden, whose sound is indebted to Isis' ''Oceanic'',<ref name=\"steff\" /> [[Amenra]] from Belgium, who signed to Neurosis' label [[Neurot Recordings]] and rival their predecessors in sheer spiritual intensity,<ref name=\"amenra\">{{cite news|url=https://www.independent.co.uk/arts-entertainment/music/features/amenra-mass-vi-album-stream-a8002161.html|title=AMENRA \u2013 MASS VI: Album Stream|last=Dedman|first=Remfry|newspaper=The Independent|date=16 October 2017|accessdate=16 October 2017}}</ref> and [[Year of No Light]] from France, who have transitioned from a sludge-oriented sound to monumental instrumental compositions, \"beautifully layered, but still dark and heavy\".<ref name=\"bandcamp\"/>\n\nAnother prominent instrumental band, [[Russian Circles]], was also strongly influenced by ''Oceanic''.<ref name=\"steff\" /> By contrast, [[True Widow]], whose sound is rooted as much in 1990s [[indie rock]] and [[psychedelic rock]] as in doom metal, offer a distinctive take on post-metal, most impactfully on the 2013's ''[[Circumambulation (album)|Circumambulation]]'', by employing \"male/female vocal interplay\" and showcasing \"vulnerability and restraint\".<ref name=\"bandcamp\"/> Meanwhile, the Melvins had made a direct mark on the sound they themselves inspired with the 2004 album ''[[Pigs of the Roman Empire]]'', a collaboration with [[dark ambient]] composer [[Lustmord]].<ref name=\"bandcamp\"/>\n\nGradually, post-metal as a genre has achieved major critical acclaim.<ref name=\"steff\" /> This was reinforced by the \"widely publicized\" success of [[Deafheaven]],<ref name=\"bandcamp\"/> whose sophomore album ''[[Sunbather (album)|Sunbather]]'' became one of the most celebrated releases of 2013. The band's successful fusion of caustic black metal with blissfull shoegazing in the vein of [[My Bloody Valentine (band)|My Bloody Valentine]] and [[Slowdive]],<ref name=\"bandcamp\"/> though preceded by the French musician [[Neige (musician)|Neige]] of [[Alcest]], was nicknamed [[blackgaze]] and met with disdain from fans of conventional [[extreme metal]]. It has also inspired a wave of bands such as [[Ghost Bath]], who often use undistorted guitar melodies to develop unsettling atmospheres, and Austria's [[Harakiri for the Sky]], whose despairing sound melds black metal and post-hardcore.<ref name=\"bandcamp\"/>\n\n[[File:Deafheaven @ A Colossal Weekend 2017 46.jpg|thumb|right|[[Deafheaven]] have brought the genre widespread critical acclaim in their fusion of [[black metal]] and [[shoegazing]].]]\n\n==Characteristics==\nPost-metal is generally heavy, aggressive, and dark, but explores a variety of musical approaches alien to conventional [[heavy metal music|heavy metal]] and [[extreme metal]].<ref name=\"bandcamp\"/> It mirrors [[post-rock]] and [[post-hardcore]] in its emphasis on atmosphere and deep emotion and may be considered abstract,<ref name=\"fact\" /> introspective,<ref name=\"steff\" /> expansive,<ref name=\"bbc1\">{{cite web | url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/music/reviews/zhj9 | title=Neurosis - Times of Grace Review | publisher=[[BBC]] | accessdate=January 5, 2016 | author=Moffitt, Greg}}</ref> [[hypnotic]],<ref name=\"gn\" /> [[progressive music|progressive]],<ref name=\"bbc1\" /> layered,<ref name=\"bandcamp\"/> or even [[Apocalypse|apocalyptic]].<ref name=\"bbc1\" /> Jon Wiederhorn writes that though some post-metal bands \"sought to break away from their raging roots by exploring less bombastic and more dynamic musical techniques\" and others \"sought to remain raw and corrosive\", their music shares a \"heavy-lidded yet eye-opening\" effect.<ref name=\"bandcamp\"/> ''[[The New York Times]]'' associated the term with a \"wave of bands using metal as a jumping-off point for a range of [[experimental music|experimental]] styles, dabbling in [[free jazz]], [[minimal music|minimalist]] post-rock, [[noise music|noise]] and even [[modern classical music]].\"<ref name=\"nyt\">{{cite news | last = Caraminica | first = Jon | url = https://www.nytimes.com/2005/09/20/arts/the-alchemy-of-artworld-heavy-metal.html | title = The alchemy of art-world heavy metal | newspaper = [[The New York Times]] | accessdate = 2005-09-20}}</ref> Contemporary post-metal bands incorporate influences ranging through [[doom metal]], [[black metal]], [[shoegazing]], [[progressive rock]], [[folk music]], and [[classical music]].<ref name=\"bandcamp\"/>\n\nWriting for [[Slate (magazine)|''Slate'']] in 2009, [[Simon Reynolds]] reflected:\n{{quote|[P]ost-rock doesn't have the same temporal aspect that [[post-disco]] or [[post-punk]] have; it's not about the ripples set in motion by a galvanizing \"event.\" Rather, it evokes a sense of \"going beyond\" the structures of a genre of music without completely abandoning its legacy of attitudes and assumptions. For similar reasons, the term post-metal seems increasingly useful to describe the vast and variegated swath of genres (the thousand flavors of doom/black/[[death metal|death]]/[[grindcore|grind]]/[[drone metal|drone]]/[[sludge metal|sludge]]/etc., ad infinitum) that emerged from the early '90s onward. Sometimes beat-free and [[ambient music|ambient]], increasingly the work of home-studio loners rather than performing bands, post-metal of the kind released by labels like [[Hydra Head Records|Hydra Head]] often seems to have barely any connection to metal as understood by, say, [[VH1 Classic]] doc-makers. The continuity is less sonic but attitudinal: the penchant for [[Fascination with death|morbidity]] and darkness taken to a sometimes hokey degree; the somber clothing and the long hair; the harrowed, indecipherably [[growled vocals]]; the bombastically verbose lyrics/song titles/band names. It's that aesthetic rather than a way of riffing or a palette of guitar sounds that ties post-metal back to [[Judas Priest]] and [[Black Sabbath]].<ref>{{cite web|title=Grunge's Long Shadow|url=http://www.slate.com/articles/arts/music_box/2009/05/grunges_long_shadow.single.html#pagebreak_anchor_2|accessdate=2010-11-14|authorlink=Simon Reynolds|work=[[Slate (magazine)|Slate]]}}</ref>}}\n\n[[File:Russian Circles - Madrid - 15 abril 2015 2.JPG|thumb|left|Many groups, including [[Russian Circles]], are [[instrumental]].]]\nPost-metal is therefore notoriously difficult to define.{{original research inline|date=September 2018}} ''[[Fact (UK magazine)|Fact]]'' writer Robin Jahdi notes that \"the best [[Neurosis (band)|Neurosis]] albums don't sound anything like the best offerings from [[Isis (band)|Isis]]\" and that the genre cannot be readily distinguished from doom metal, modern black metal, and [[progressive metal]], \"[taking] in all of these elements without being entirely any one of them\".<ref name=\"fact\">{{cite web | url=http://www.factmag.com/2015/06/24/40-best-post-metal/ | title=The 40 best post-metal records ever made | work=[[Fact (UK magazine)|Fact]] | date=June 24, 2015 | accessdate=November 11, 2017 | author=Jahdi, Robin}}</ref> Contemporary post-metal is often seen as combining \"elements of doom metal, sludge, and/or black metal with elements of post-rock and shoegaze\", being more \"peaceful\" than metal but retaining its dark theming and [[screaming (music)|harsh vocal style]].<ref name=\"steff\" /> As with post-rock, however, many bands are [[instrumental]] and when vocals are used, they often \"resemble [another] accompanying instrument\" rather than actual words.<ref name=\"steff\" /> Songs are typically long and employ [[crescendo]]s, gradually building upon repeated [[Theme (music)|theme]]s; [[Aaron Turner]] of Isis stated that \"the standard song format of [[Verse\u2013chorus form|verse-chorus-verse-chorus]] is something that has been done and redone, and it seems pointless to adhere to that structure when there are so many other avenues to explore\".<ref name=\"isisguitar\">{{cite magazine\n| last = Porosky | first = Pamela | url = http://www.guitarplayer.com/story.asp?storyCode=78 | archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20160304072104/http://www.guitarplayer.com/story.asp?storyCode=78 | url-status = dead | archive-date = 2016-03-04 | title = Aaron Turner and Michael Gallagher interview | magazine = [[Guitar Player]] | accessdate = 2006-09-06}} {{dead link|date=November 2017}}</ref>\n\n===Aesthetic and culture===\nWhile Simon Reynolds locates the connection between post-metal and conventional metal in attitude and aesthetic over musical approach, others have emphasized differences in these very areas.{{failed verification|date=September 2018}} Noting the divergence from typical [[metal fashion]], ''[[The New York Times]]'' described a 2005 [[Pelican (band)|Pelican]] show at the [[Knitting Factory]] in [[New York City]]: \"Instead of long hair and all-black outfits, the crowd was displaying the trappings of brainy, slightly nerdy [[indie rock]]. Young men wore artistically cropped hair and [[Slim-fit pants|tight-legged jeans]], and there was even a smattering of young women in librarian glasses and worn-out [[Chuck Taylor All-Stars|Chuck Taylor]] sneakers.\"<ref name=\"nyt\" /> Jon Wiederhorn describes the post-metal scene as a \"global community of artists\" positioned on the \"fringes of the [[underground music|underground]].\"<ref name=\"bandcamp\"/> Pelican's Trevor de Brauw stated in 2007:<ref>{{cite web | url = http://www.drownedinsound.com/articles/1801290 | title = Pelican: \"We're neither trend setters nor trend followers\" | first = Mike | last = Diver | work = [[Drowned in Sound]] | date = 2007-03-27 | accessdate = 2007-03-29}}</ref>\n\n[[File:Pelican performing at Sant Feliu Fest 2004.jpg|thumb|[[Pelican (band)|Pelican]], also instrumental, diverge from [[heavy metal music|heavy metal]] conventions in all aspects of their style and approach.]]\n{{quote|I have an affinity [f]or metal, but I don't think of Pelican as a metal band. So when people call us 'instrumetal', or post-metal, or [[metalcore]] or whatever, I can see why they say that, but it's not something that I feel a close connection with. I feel we're part of a community with some bands \u2013 [[Mono (Japanese band)|Mono]] are good friends of ours, but I don't feel that we're that similar musically. Their music is more similar to classical music, whereas I feel ours has more in common with [[punk rock|punk]] and [[hardcore punk|hardcore]].|sign=|source=}}\n\n==List of bands==\n{{columns-list|colwidth=15em|\n\n'''A'''\n* [[A Hope for Home]]<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.absolutepunk.net/showthread.php?t=1618762|title=chorus.fm|website=chorus.fm}}</ref>\n* [[Agalloch]]<ref name=\"bandcamp\"/>\n* [[Alcest]]<ref>{{cite magazine | url=https://www.rollingstone.com/music/pictures/10-new-artists-you-need-to-know-january-2014-20140124/alcest-0034319 | title=Alcest | magazine=[[Rolling Stone]] | accessdate=15 April 2015 | author=Grow, Kory}}</ref><ref name=\"CoS\">{{Cite news|url=http://consequenceofsound.net/2016/11/the-top-10-metal-albums-of-2016/full-post/|title=The Top 10 Metal Albums of 2016|last1=Barry|first1=Sean|first2=Jon|last2=Hadusek|newspa