{"title_page": "Jas Ram Singh", "text_new": "[[Lieutenant colonel|Lieutenant Colonel]] (1st March 1935) '''Jas Ram Singh''', [[Ashoka Chakra (military decoration)|AC]] was a retired [[Indian Army]] Officer and recipient of [[Ashoka Chakra (military decoration)|Ashoka Chakra]] the India's highest peace time military decoration.<ref>{{Cite web|url=PREVIEW\n4:40\nAshok Chakra Awardee Lt Col Jasram Singh's Inspiring Story {{!}} Bravery\nYouTube \u00b7 NationalDefence\nJan 30, 2018|title=|last=|first=|date=|website=|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref> \n\n== Early Life ==\nLt Col Jas Ram Singh was born on 1st March 1935 at Bhabokra village in Bulandshahr District of Uttar Pradesh. His father, Shri Badan Singh was a simple farmer and instilled in his children honesty, integrity and simple living. In the absence of basic facilities and even a primary school in his village, Lt Col Jas Ram Singh had to struggle in his childhood. He had his primary education in another village after which he joined NREC in Khurja for his higher education.\n\n== Military Career ==\nHe joined the Army as a Signalman. After serving in a number of Signal Regiments, he was selected as an instructor in the [[Army Educational Corps]] where he continued till 1963. In the same year, he was commissioned as an Emergency Commissioned Officer from OTS, Madras into the [[Rajput Regiment]].\n\n== Operation in Mizo Hills ==\nIn 1968 Captain Jas Ram Singh was posted with [[Rajput Regiment]] in [[Mizoram]]. In the same year he was leading 16 Battalion\u2019s platoon of  Rajput Regiment in Mizo Hills. He received information that some militants were hidden in Mizo hills. After  receiving the information, he tried hard and came to know that near about 50 militants were present in a village in Mizo Hills. Captain Jasram Singh along with two platoons instantly headed towards the village. When they were about to reach the village, the platoons came under heavy militants fire from a dominating feature. Captain Jasram Singh individually led the assault and overran the militants \u2018position. After this courageous act militants abandoned position and fled away. They left behind two dead, six injured and a huge quantity of arms and ammunition. In this complete encounter, Captain Jasram Singh displayed most conspicuous bravery and leadership. For his bravery he received [[Ashoka Chakra (military decoration)|Ashoka Chakra Award]]. \n\n<br />\n\n== Reference ==\n<references />\n\n\n\n<br /><br />\n", "text_old": "[[Lieutenant colonel|Lieutenant Colonel]] '''Jas Ram Singh''', [[Ashoka Chakra (military decoration)|AC]] was a retired [[Indian Army]] Officer and recipient of [[Ashoka Chakra (military decoration)|Ashoka Chakra]] the India's highest peace time military decoration.<ref>{{Cite web|url=PREVIEW\n4:40\nAshok Chakra Awardee Lt Col Jasram Singh's Inspiring Story {{!}} Bravery\nYouTube \u00b7 NationalDefence\nJan 30, 2018|title=|last=|first=|date=|website=|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref> \n\n== Early Life ==\nLt Col Jas Ram Singh was born on 1st March 1935 at Bhabokra village in Bulandshahr District of Uttar Pradesh. His father, Shri Badan Singh was a simple farmer and instilled in his children honesty, integrity and simple living. In the absence of basic facilities and even a primary school in his village, Lt Col Jas Ram Singh had to struggle in his childhood. He had his primary education in another village after which he joined NREC in Khurja for his higher education.\n\n== Military Career ==\nHe joined the Army as a Signalman. After serving in a number of Signal Regiments, he was selected as an instructor in the [[Army Educational Corps]] where he continued till 1963. In the same year, he was commissioned as an Emergency Commissioned Officer from OTS, Madras into the [[Rajput Regiment]].\n\n== Operation in Mizo Hills ==\nIn 1968 Captain Jas Ram Singh was posted with [[Rajput Regiment]] in [[Mizoram]]. In the same year he was leading 16 Battalion\u2019s platoon of  Rajput Regiment in Mizo Hills. He received information that some militants were hidden in Mizo hills. After  receiving the information, he tried hard and came to know that near about 50 militants were present in a village in Mizo Hills. Captain Jasram Singh along with two platoons instantly headed towards the village. When they were about to reach the village, the platoons came under heavy militants fire from a dominating feature. Captain Jasram Singh individually led the assault and overran the militants \u2018position. After this courageous act militants abandoned position and fled away. They left behind two dead, six injured and a huge quantity of arms and ammunition. In this complete encounter, Captain Jasram Singh displayed most conspicuous bravery and leadership. For his bravery he received [[Ashoka Chakra (military decoration)|Ashoka Chakra Award]]. \n\n<br />\n\n== Reference ==\n<references />\n\n\n\n<br /><br />\n", "name_user": "Koushik Pain", "label": "safe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Jas_Ram_Singh"}
{"title_page": "Isabella, Countess of Vertus", "text_new": "{{Use dmy dates|date=April 2020}}\n{{Infobox royalty\n| name         =Isabella \n| title = Countess of Vertus\n| image        = Isabella of Valois (1348\u20131372).png\n| image_size = 190px\n| caption      = \n| spouse       =[[Gian Galeazzo Visconti]]\n| issue        =Gian Galeazzo Visconti<br/>Azzone Visconti<br/>[[Valentina Visconti, Duchess of Orl\u00e9ans|Valentina, Duchess of Orl\u00e9ans]]<br/>Carlo Visconti\n| full name    =\n| house = [[House of Valois|Valois]]\n| father       =[[John II of France]]\n| mother       =[[Bonne of Bohemia]]\n| birth_date   =1 October 1348\n| birth_place  =Ch\u00e2teau de [[Bois de Vincennes]], France\n| death_date   ={{death date and age|1373|9|11|1348|10|1|df=y}}\n| death_place  =[[Pavia]]\n}}\n'''Isabella of France''' (1 October 1348 &ndash; 11 September 1373) was a French [[princess]] and member of the [[House of Valois]], as well as the wife of [[Gian Galeazzo Visconti]], who after her death became [[List of rulers of Milan|Duke of Milan]].\n\nBorn in [[Bois de Vincennes]], Isabella was the youngest daughter of King [[John II of France]] by his first wife, [[Bonne of Bohemia]].<ref name=lundy>{{Cite web\n  | last = Lundy\n  | first = Darryl\n  | title = The Peerage: Isabel de Valois\n  | url=http://www.thepeerage.com/p11365.htm\n  | accessdate = 28 September 2009 }}</ref>\n\nHer maternal uncle Count [[Amadeus VI of Savoy]] arranged her marriage with [[Gian Galeazzo Visconti]]. As her dowry, Isabella received the county of [[Sommi\u00e8res]], exchanged later for the county of [[Vertus]]. On 8 October 1360, Isabella and Gian Galeazzo were married in Milan, and six months later, in April 1361, she was declared sovereign Countess of Vertus. The couple had four children:<ref>[http://www.storiadimilano.it/Personaggi/Visconti/visconti.htm#Gian Galeazzo ''Gian Galeazzo'' in: Storiadimilano.it] [retrieved 12 September 2014].</ref>\n*Gian Galeazzo (b. Pavia, 4 March 1366 \u2013 d. bef. 1376).\n*Azzone (b. Pavia, 1368 \u2013 d. Pavia, 4 October 1381).\n*[[Valentina Visconti, Duchess of Orl\u00e9ans|Valentina]] (b. Pavia, 1371 \u2013 d. Ch\u00e2teau de Blois, Loir-et-Cher, 14 December 1408), married on 17 August 1389 to [[Louis I, Duke of Orl\u00e9ans]]\n*Carlo (b. Pavia, 11 September 1373 \u2013 d. Pavia, 1374).\n\nIsabella died in childbirth in [[Pavia]] in 1373.<ref name=lundy/><ref>{{MLCC |warning=1 |url=http://fmg.ac/Projects/MedLands/CAPET.htm#Isabelledied1373 |title-date= |title= CAPET|date=August 2012}}</ref>\n\n==Family tree of Isabella of Vertus==\n{{ahnentafel\n|collapsed=yes |align=center\n|boxstyle_1=background-color: #fcc;\n|boxstyle_2=background-color: #fb9;\n|boxstyle_3=background-color: #ffc;\n|boxstyle_4=background-color: #bfc;\n|boxstyle_5=background-color: #9fe;\n| 1= 1. '''Isabelle of Valois'''\n| 2= 2. [[John II of France]]\n| 3= 3. [[Bonne of Bohemia]]\n| 4= 4. [[Philip VI of France]]\n| 5= 5. [[Joan the Lame]]\n| 6= 6. [[John I of Bohemia]]\n| 7= 7. [[Elisabeth of Bohemia (1292\u20131330)]]\n| 8= 8. [[Charles of Valois]]\n| 9= 9. [[Marguerite of Anjou and Maine]]\n|10= 10. [[Robert II, Duke of Burgundy]]\n|11= 11. [[Agnes of France, Duchess of Burgundy]]\n|12= 12. [[Henry VII, Holy Roman Emperor]]\n|13= 13. [[Margaret of Brabant]]\n|14= 14. [[Wenceslaus II of Bohemia]]\n|15= 15. [[Judith of Habsburg]]\n|16= 16. [[Philip III of France]]\n|17= 17. [[Isabella of Aragon, Queen of France|Isabella of Aragon]]\n|18= 18. [[Charles II of Naples]]\n|19= 19. [[Maria of Hungary (1257\u20131323)|Maria Arpad of Hungary]]\n|20= 20. [[Hugh IV, Duke of Burgundy]]\n|21= 21. [[Yolande of Dreux (Burgundy)|Yolande of Dreux]]\n|22= 22. [[Louis IX of France]]\n|23= 23. [[Marguerite of Provence]]\n|24= 24. [[Henry VI of Luxembourg]]\n|25= 25. [[Beatrice d'Avesnes]]\n|26= 26. [[John I, Duke of Brabant]]\n|27= 27. [[Margaret III, Countess of Flanders]]\n|28= 28. [[Ottokar II of Bohemia]]\n|29= 29. [[Kunigunda of Slavonia]]\n|30= 31. [[Rudo